name: Dev Rishi
review_text:
Agra Fort is a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts and travelers alike. This UNESCO World Heritage site offers a glimpse into the grandeur of the Mughal Empire. The massive red sandstone walls, intricate architecture, and beautiful courtyards provide a perfect blend of history and beauty. Don't miss iconic spots like the Diwan-i-Am, Diwan-i-Khas, and Jahangirs Palace. The fort also offers stunning views of the Taj Mahal across the Yamuna River. A guided tour is recommended to truly appreciate its rich history. Ideal for photography and exploring Mughal heritage!

Public holiday

name: Vaishnavi Bhoir
review_text:
Agra Fort is a magnificent piece of architecture, rich in history and culture. As soon as you step in, you are transported back in time, with its intricate carvings, majestic gates, and expansive courtyards. The fort offers stunning views of the Taj Mahal from certain points, adding to its allure. Walking through the halls and gardens, you can feel the grandeur of the Mughal era. The well-preserved structures, like the Diwan-i-Aam and Diwan-i-Khas, are a must-see. A visit to Agra Fort is a captivating journey through Indias royal past, and its a must-visit for history and architecture enthusiasts.
Visited on
Weekday

name: Ln sharma
review_text: This fort was given a new grand look by renovating the Badalgarh fort built by Meena Raja Badal of the ancient Matsya Mahajanapada by the feudal lord of Kashi Kanyakubj i.e. Varanasi Kannauj dynasty, which was modernized in 1504 by Sultan Sikandar Lodi and then by Akbar to the present form and Agra Fort. Name was given. The original dynasty of Kachwaha Shekhawats of Rajasthan started from this fort. Those who went to Narwar from here reached Dausa and then Amber i.e. present day Jaipur.

name: Masharib Taslim
review_text:
I recently visited Agra Fort, and it was an incredible experience! This UNESCO world heritage site is a stunning red sandstone fortress that really takes you back in time. As soon as I entered, I was amazed by the impressive walls and beautiful gardens.

Walking through the fort, I explored places like the Diwan-e-Khas, which showcase the luxury of the Mughal Era. The views of the Taj Mahal from the Fort are absolutely breathtaking.

This site is well- maintained and I appreciated having a knowledgeable guide who shared interesting stories about its history. I recommend visiting early in the morning to enjoy the peaceful atmosphere and avoid the crowds.

Overall, Agra Fort is a must- see if youre in Agra. Its a perfect blend of beauty and history and I left with unforgettable memories Dont miss it!

review_text:
Agra Fort is a famous historical building. It is a symbol of the glory of the Mughal emperors. There are some grand and beautiful buildings inside this fort like - Diwane Khas, Anguri Mahal, Nagina Masjid, Moti Masjid etc.The Bengali Palace or Akbari Mahal was a beautiful palace located in the Agra Fort of which only ruins now remain. It is said that this was Akbars harem, here he used to keep 5000 of his women.

name: prasanth P
review_text:
Hey hi guys,

This is Prasanth Gupta (Instagram Id:- @Solo_travelleer ).

Historical background :-
In 1530 by the Mughal emperor humayun .
In 1573 it was renovated by the Mughal emperor Akbar.
One of the major forts in India which faced many dynasties invasion.
In the middle of 1980s UNESCO was recognised as a world heritage site.

Important places :-
--> Jahangir hauz,
--> shahjahani mahal,
--> Ghazin gate,
--> shish mahal,etc.

Agra fort is also known as Agra red Fort.
If youre visiting Agra never miss this fort to visit.
Not in the summers please.

name: PrisTine GaMer
review_text:
Visiting Agra Fort was a fantastic experience! The architecture is truly impressive, with its massive red sandstone walls and intricate details showcasing the grandeur of the Mughal era. Walking through the halls and courtyards feels like stepping back in time, with each section narrating stories of emperors and their legacy.

The fort is well-maintained, and the views of the Taj Mahal from certain points add to the beauty. Guides are available, and their stories make the visit even more engaging. Just be ready for a bit of walking, as the fort is vast. Highly recommend visiting this historical gem for anyone in Agra!

name: Nayan Raut
review_text:
Agra Fort is an iconic fortress with a rich history, and visiting it feels like stepping into the past. Located in Agra, this UNESCO World Heritage Site is a masterpiece of Mughal architecture. The fort is massive, covering about 94 acres, and is made primarily from red sandstone, giving it a regal and imposing look.

As you enter through the grand Amar Singh Gate, you are greeted by the high, thick walls that have protected this fort for centuries. Once inside, its like entering a small city, with courtyards, palaces, mosques, and gardens scattered around. The fort served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors until the mid-17th century, and you can sense the grandeur of their era here.

One of the most impressive buildings inside is the Jahangir Mahal, which is a blend of Hindu and Central Asian architectural styles. This palace is richly decorated with intricate carvings and was built as a residence for the royal women.

Then theres the Diwan-i-Am (Hall of Public Audience), where the emperor would meet his subjects and hear their grievances. You can almost imagine the grandeur of these gatherings with the emperor seated on his throne, listening to the petitions of his people.

The Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience), where the emperor held private meetings, has beautifully ornate pillars and is where you can find the famous Peacock Throne once stood. From here, you get a breathtaking view of the Taj Mahal in the distance, a sight that would have been enjoyed by the Mughal rulers as well.

Overall, it was full exploring insight through out the day. If you have interest in earlier heritage must visit then.

Weekend

name: TUSHAR KUMAR
review_text:
The second best place in Agra after the Taj Mahal. The fortification of the whole area is just breathtaking. The monuments inside the fort are made up of redstone and white marbles. You will witness the indo-islamic Architectural work in the fort.

Entry and exit both are from the Amar singh gate.
Entry time:- Sunrise to sunset
Cloakroom is available but you can carry your bags inside, food is strictly not allowed inside.
Ticket price is 50 and 5 rs discount when Booked online.
Do carry a bottle of water bcoz you will need it as the area of the fort is very large and you have to give at least 1.5 to 2 hours of time to explore it properly.
Its just within the walking distance from Agra fort railway station.

name: Ragesh VT
review_text:
Agra Fort built in 1565 by Mughal Emperor Akbar, the fort was initially made of red sandstone and later modified by Shah Jahan also known as Lal Qila or Red Fort, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and one of Indias most iconic monuments. Located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, its a testament to Mughal architecture and engineering and a blend of Indian, Persian, and Islamic styles, with:

1. Red sandstone walls

2. Marble and stone inlays

3. Intricate carvings and calligraphy

4. Symmetrical gardens and water features

The Main Attractions are

1. Diwan-i-Khas (Private Audience Hall)

2. Diwan-i-Am (Public Audience Hall)

3. Khas Mahal (Private Palace)

4. Sheesh Mahal (Mirror Palace)

5. Jahangirs Palace

6. Akbars Mausoleum

7. Mina Masjid (Heavenly Mosque)

Timings : 6:00 AM - 7:00 PM (April-September), 6:00 AM - 5:00 PM (October-March). Entry Fee: 550 (foreigners), 50 (Indians). Online and offline ticket bookings are available. Hire a licensed guide for insightful commentary and better understanding about the monument. Photography is allowed, but no flash or tripods allowed

Nearest airport is Agra airport (7 km)

and railway station is Agra Cantonment Railway Station (5 km).

Nearby Attractions are :-

1. Taj Mahal (2.5 km)

2. Fatehpur Sikri (35 km)

3. Itmad-Ud-Daulahs Tomb (4 km)

4. Akbars Mausoleum (8 km)

You can do it from outside, but I would like you to come in if you can.

It is not suitable for people with walking disabilities as it involves going up and down hills and stairs.
There are also places where you can see the Taj Mahal in the distance.

name: Azaharin Abd Latiff
review_text:
A wonderful experience visiting Agra Fort and understanding the history of the Moghul empire era. The place is a UNESCO heritage site and full of Moghul empire history.

Each corner of the fort represented by its gates into the fort tells a related story from the Mughal era. It was also the site of the Shah Jahan that inpires Taj Mahal was incarcerated to his death.

You'll need to walk a bit to cover the entire fort, but it's definitely worth it to explore the beautiful architecture and learn about its past. Just be cautious as some areas smelled fuming stinky urine kind of smell.

Well architectured fort built with purpose. A nice view of the Taj Mahal and the river at one corner of the fort. The Fort seems to contain elements of Moghul, Islamic and Persian in its design and architecture, which is impressive.

Well preserved heritage site however externally it's dusty and dirty. In some areas externally it is unhygienic and produce bad stinky fuming odour in the air.

All in all, Agra Fort is a must-visit if youre in the area. Just take precautions of the shortcomings mentioned.
Visited on
Weekday

name: Chirag Yadav
review_text:
Agra Fort: A Majestic Marvel of Mughal Architecture
Agra Fort, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, is a magnificent monument that stands as a testament to the grandeur of the Mughal Empire. Located in Agra, India, this imposing fortress is a must-visit for history buffs and architecture enthusiasts.
Key Highlights:
* Impressive Architecture: The fort showcases the finest examples of Mughal architecture, with intricate carvings, ornate arches, and beautiful gardens.
* Historical Significance: Agra Fort was the seat of power for several Mughal emperors, including Akbar, Shah Jahan, and Aurangzeb. It witnessed many significant events in Indian history.
* Stunning Views: The fort offers breathtaking panoramic views of the Taj Mahal, the Yamuna River, and the surrounding city.
* Interesting Attractions: Within the forts walls, visitors can explore various attractions such as the Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience), Diwan-i-Am (Hall of Public Audience), Moti Masjid (Pearl Mosque), and the Khas Mahal (Private Palace).
Overall, Agra Fort is a must-see destination for anyone visiting Agra. Its rich history, stunning architecture, and breathtaking views make it a truly unforgettable experience.
Have you visited Agra Fort? What was your favorite part of the experience?

name: Adrian Corera
review_text:
The history of Agra Fort can be traced back to 1504 when it was occupied by the Lodhi Dynasty up until 1526 when the Mughals captured it and Emperor Humayun was coronated here. Emperor Akbar carried out extensive renovation, giving it the present appearance.
The Fort is made of red sandstone and hence also referred to as Agras Lal Qila or Red Fort.
There are four gates the Delhi Gate, the Lahore Gate, Akbar Gate and the Khizri Gate opening on to the River Yamuna.
The Delhi Gate is not accessible to the public as the military occupies the northern part of the Fort.
The Fort itself comprises of the Akbar and Jehangir Mahal residential complex, Shah Jehani Mahal of white marble overlooking the Yamuna and from where the imprisoned Shah Jehan could see the Taj Mahal, the Shish Mahal also built by Shah Jehan with exquisite glass mosaic work.
Theres an amazing optical illusion of the Taj Mahal when viewed from the Agra Fort. If you stand near the railing of the Shah Jehani Mahal overlooking the Yamuna River, the Taj Mahal looks farther and smaller, but as you move away, across the lawn to the side opposite tge Taj Mahal suddenly stands out looking much bigger in size and closer than it really is. It was an awesome experience to be cherished. However, this illusion can not be captured on camera because cameras capture reality, not illusions.
It was an amazing experience to visit the Fort and marvel at the grandeur of these majestic buildings.

name: kenugawa
review_text:
**Agra Fort** is a huge fort located in Agra, northern India, and is an important historical structure built during the Mughal era. It is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site and is located close to Agras other famous monument, the Taj Mahal.

### Historical background
- **Year of construction**: The first construction took place in the 16th century, specifically during the reign of Akbar the Great (1565).
- **Builder**: Mughal Emperor Akbar.
- **Purpose of use**: Agra Fort was used as the imperial palace of the Mughal Empire, serving as a royal residence, military base, and political center.

### Architectural features
- **Material**: Mainly composed of red sandstone, also known as Red Fort. Parts of it were later renovated with white marble.
- **Extensive grounds**: Agra Fort is surrounded by a 2.5-kilometer thick wall that is dotted with palaces, mosques, and gardens.
- **Complex Architectural Style**: Agra Forts buildings are constructed in a complex style that incorporates the Islamic design characteristic of Mughal architecture, as well as Hindu and Persian influences.

### Main buildings and attractions
1. **Jahangir Mahal**:
- A palace built by Emperor Akbar the Great for his son Jahangir. It features beautiful red sandstone decoration and a large courtyard.

2. **Musamman Burj**:
- This is the tower where Shah Jahan was imprisoned, and is famous for being the place where you can see the Taj Mahal in the distance. From here, Shah Jahan spent his final years admiring the Taj Mahal, which he built for his beloved wife Mumtaz Mahal.

3. **Shah Jahan Mahal**:
- This elegant palace is covered in white marble and exhibits the typical opulence of Mughal architecture.

4. **Shish Mahal**:
- Also known as the ``Palace of Mirrors, this is a building with ornate interior decoration decorated with mirrors.

5. **Diwan-i-Aam**:
- It was used as a public audience room, where the emperor interacted with his subjects.

6. **Diwan-i-Khas**:
- A luxurious room for the emperor and special guests.

### Historical significance
- Agra Fort not only symbolized the prosperity of the Mughal Empire, but was also an important political and military base. It was also the place where Shah Jahan was imprisoned by his son Aurangzeb, and the scene of internal conflict in the Mughal Empire.
- Also, **along with the Taj Mahal**, it attracts many tourists as one of Indias leading tourist destinations.

### Sightseeing highlights
- Agra Fort is a vast site with several palaces, gardens, and audience halls scattered throughout. Therefore, you can enjoy the harmony of beautiful architecture and nature while learning about historical episodes.
- Also, from the top of the castle walls, you can see the Taj Mahal in the distance, so the romantic view is also a highlight of sightseeing.

Agra Fort is a place worth visiting to experience the great history and magnificent architecture of the Mughal Empire.

name: Dewan Asif
review_text:
Agra Fort is a stunning architectural masterpiece built by Emperor Akbar in the 16th century. It served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors and played a key role in Indias history. A large canal was built nearby for security purposes.

The fort is a crowded place, known for its beautiful gardens and panoramic views of the Taj Mahal. Visitors can enjoy a glimpse of the Taj from within the fort. An entrance fee is required, and its important to be cautious of scams near the entrance. The fort is a must-visit for its rich history and magnificent design.

name: Dinesh Patil
review_text:
This is a historical fort in the city of Agra. This place is also known as Agra Red fort. It is built by Humayun and It was later renewed by the Mughal emperor Akbar from 1573. It was the main residency of the Mughal dynasty until 1638, when the capital was shifted from Agra to Delhi. To go there various transport facilities available including train, bus, auto, horses vehicle, etc. Before being captured by Britishers, the last Indian rural was Marathas. It is an unesco world heritage site because of its importance. It is also renowned for Shah Jahan. This place is very beautiful. And there are lots of things to see. The Taj Mahal is clearly visible from this fort.

name: Rahul Sharma
review_text:
Agra Fort is a testament to the grandeur and opulence of the Mughal Empire.
This iconic red sandstone fort, located in Agra, India, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and offers a fascinating glimpse into the rich history of the Mughal dynasty. With its imposing walls, intricate carvings, and stunning courtyards, Agra Fort is a must-visit for history buffs and architecture enthusiasts.
Here are some key highlights of my experience:
* The Diwan-i-Khas: This hall of private audience is a masterpiece of Mughal architecture, featuring a beautifully carved central pillar and stunning inlaid work.
* The Moti Masjid: This white marble mosque is a symbol of Mughal elegance and is known for its intricate carvings and peaceful atmosphere.
* The Jahangiri Mahal: This palace complex was built by Akbar for his son, Jahangir, and offers a glimpse into the luxurious lifestyle of the Mughal rulers.
* The Musamman Burj: This octagonal tower, located on the Yamuna River, offers breathtaking views of the Taj Mahal and the surrounding countryside.
Overall, my visit to Agra Fort was a truly unforgettable experience. The forts rich history, stunning architecture, and serene atmosphere made it a highlight.

name: Karthik Kumar Gajam
review_text:
Agra Fort is an architectural masterpiece that offers a glimpse into the grandeur of the Mughal era. The fort is massive, with beautiful red sandstone walls, intricate carvings, and stunning palaces inside. Exploring the vast grounds can take a few hours, so it's a good idea to wear comfortable shoes and carry a water bottle to stay hydrated.

Hiring a guide is highly recommended to fully appreciate the fort's rich history, fascinating stories, and hidden details. The guide can help you understand the significance of various structures like the Diwan-i-Aam, Diwan-i-Khas, and the Khas Mahal.

One of the highlights is the breathtaking view of the Taj Mahal from the balconies of the fort, offering a unique and picturesque perspective of the iconic monument across the Yamuna River. To avoid the long lines, book your tickets online in advance.

Overall, Agra Fort is a must-visit for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply wanting to enjoy some beautiful views of the Taj Mahal.

name: Manish Saini
review_text:
This fort is located in the city of Agra, a historic fortress dating back to the 11th century. This architectural marvel was honed under the reigns of Jahangir and Shah Jahan started in 1565. The fort echoes the blend of Mughal, Persian, and Hindu styles built with Red Sandstone. The reach of the walls is up to 70 feet encircling about 94 acres. This fort houses palaces of Jahangir, built by Akbar, reflecting the fusion of Islamic and Hindu designs. The beautiful and glimmering 'Sheesh Mahal' is a mirrored palace with ceilings and walls to behold within its weaving reflections. A place of historical stories, this offers panoramic views of the Taj Mahal which is located near the Yamuna River.

name: Alan Mathews
review_text:
I had a wonderful experience visiting Agra Fort! The place is steeped in history, and each corner of the fort seems to tell a story from the Mughal era. You'll need to walk a bit to cover the entire fort, but it's definitely worth it to explore the beautiful architecture and learn about its past.
One thing to note is that theres no need to hire an expensive guide. The information boards and your own exploration can give you a good understanding of the forts significance. Plus, if you plan your visit right, you can also cover the nearby Baby Taj and the iconic Taj Mahal on the same day. These three spots are quite close to each other, making it easy to explore them all in one go.
All in all, Agra Fort is a must-visit if youre in the area.

name: A NAYAK
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort, is located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh. This is a very huge fort which is situated on the banks of Yamuna river. This fort was built by Akbar in 1565. There are many beautiful palaces, temples  and gardens in this fort.

This fort was declared a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in 2007. This fort is famous for its architecture and historical importance. This fort is a popular destination for tourists and lakhs of people visit it every year.

I hope you liked this information.

Thanks ....

name: The One Suraj
review_text:
(c)   
A majestic piece of history! Agra Fort is an awe-inspiring monument that showcases the grandeur of Mughal architecture. The intricate marble work, the imposing red sandstone walls, and the beautifully manicured gardens will leave you spellbound. The forts rich history, which dates back to the 16th century, can be felt in every nook and corner.

The guides are knowledgeable and provide valuable insights into the forts significance. The sound and light show in the evening is a must-watch!

Tips:

- Wear comfortable shoes as youll be doing a lot of walking
- Carry water and snacks to keep yourself hydrated and energized
- Try to avoid visiting during peak sun hours
- Respect the monuments rules and regulations

A must-visit attraction in Agra, and indeed, India!

name: Akshay K
review_text: !!Beware of Fraud Guides,Indias Curse!!Agra Fort is a historic fortification located in Agra, India. Constructed primarily during the Mughal Empire, it was built by Emperor Akbar in the late 16th century. The fort is renowned for its impressive architecture and serves as a significant example of Mughal military and cultural achievements. It features a series of massive walls, gates, and several notable structures inside, including the Jahangir Palace, Khas Mahal, and the Diwan-i-Am. Agra Fort is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and offers spectacular views of the nearby Taj Mahal.

name: Miguel Carlos Cuadrado
review_text: It is a defensive fort, also known as Red Fort for its peculiar construction in local sandstone and is one of the must-see places in Agra. Only a large part of its interior can be visited, but another large part belongs to the army and cannot be seen. A visit with a guide is essential since there is a lot of history within its walls.
review_translated_text: Se trata de un fuerte defensivo, tambien conocido como Fuerte Rojo por su peculiar construccion en arenisca local y es un de los lugares de visita obligada en Agra. Solo es visitable una gran parte de su interior, pero otra gran parte es del ejercito y no se puede ver. Imprescindible la visita con un guia ya que hay mucha historia entre sus murallas.

name: Surya vats
review_text:
Agra Fort, a UNESCO World Heritage site, is a masterpiece of Mughal architecture and a must-visit for history enthusiasts exploring Agra. Located just 2.5 kilometers from the iconic Taj Mahal, this majestic red sandstone fort offers a fascinating glimpse into Indias rich history.

The forts massive walls, stretching over 2.5 kilometers, enclose a complex of stunning palaces, mosques, and audience halls. The blend of Islamic and Hindu architectural styles is evident in the intricate carvings and detailed marble inlays found throughout the fort. Among the highlights is the Diwan-i-Aam (Hall of Public Audience), where the Mughal emperors addressed the public, and the Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience), a more intimate space adorned

name: Kunal prince
review_text:
Agra Fort is a remarkable example of Mughal architecture and history. The fort's massive red sandstone walls and intricate details offer a deep insight into the grandeur of the Mughal Empire.

Key attractions within the fort, like the Diwan-i-Khas, Diwan-i-Am, and Jahangir's Palace, are meticulously designed and well-preserved, reflecting the artistry of the time. The panoramic view of the Taj Mahal from the fort is breathtaking. A visit to Agra Fort is not just a journey through history but also an experience of the rich legacy left behind by the Mughals.

Although inside the fort, it has become a luxurious home for bats.

name: shaan john
review_text:
Agra Fort, an imposing red sandstone fortress, epitomizes Mughal architectural brilliance and historical significance. Built in the 16th century during Emperor Akbars reign, this grand structure offers insight into the opulent lifestyle of the Mughal emperors. Its expansive courtyards, intricate carvings, and elegant palaces, including Jahangir Mahal and Diwan-i-Khas, reflect the eras exquisite craftsmanship.

The forts formidable defensive walls encircle a vast complex of buildings and gardens, providing a striking contrast to its refined interiors. Additionally, the fort offers spectacular views of the nearby Taj Mahal, enhancing its appeal. Agra Forts rich history and architectural splendor make it an essential destination for anyone interested in Indias cultural heritage.

name: Akhmad Fajar
review_text:
Heritage of Agra

Agra Fort is a historical fort located in the city of Agra, India. This fort is a UNESCO World Heritage site and has a rich history. Here is a summary of its history:

Initial Construction: The fort was originally built by Sultan Sikandar Lodi of the Lodi Dynasty in the late 15th century, around 1565. However, the original structure was expanded and strengthened by the Mughal Emperor Akbar in 1565. Akbar moved the Mughal capital to Agra and started construction of forts on a larger scale.

Design and Structure: Agra Fort is an impressive fort, made of red stone and surrounded by high walls. The fort has two main gates--Delhi Gate and Amar Singh Gate. Inside the fort there are various important structures such as palaces, mosques and halls. Some of the famous buildings in it include the Khas Mahal (Special Palace), Diwan-i-Aam (Public Hall), and Diwan-i-Khas (Special Hall).

Role in Mughal History: Agra Fort served as the administrative center and imperial residence during the Mughal period. This fort was a strategic location that controlled important trade routes and was a center of political power.

Continued Development: Emperor Shah Jahan, Akbars successor, also carried out a number of expansions and renovations at Agra Fort. He added several beautiful marble structures, such as the Moti Mosque and luxurious palaces. Shah Jahan also moved the capital to Delhi in 1648, and after that, Agra Fort was no longer the main center of power.

Decline: After the Mughal period, Agra Fort fell into decline and some parts fell into disrepair. The fort later fell into the hands of the Maratha rulers and was finally conquered by the British in the 19th century.

Maintenance: Agra Fort was recognized as a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1983 for its historical and architectural value. Restoration and maintenance work is being carried out to maintain and preserve the fort as one of the important monuments of India.

Agra Fort is an example that reflects the power and splendor of the Mughal Dynasty and the strategic role it played in Indian history.

review_translated_text:
Heritage of Agra


Agra Fort adalah sebuah benteng bersejarah yang terletak di kota Agra, India. Benteng ini merupakan salah satu situs Warisan Dunia UNESCO dan memiliki sejarah yang kaya. Berikut adalah ringkasan sejarahnya:


Pembangunan Awal: Benteng ini awalnya dibangun oleh Sultan Sikandar Lodi dari Dinasti Lodi pada akhir abad ke-15, sekitar tahun 1565. Namun, struktur asli ini diperluas dan diperkuat oleh Kaisar Mughal Akbar pada tahun 1565. Akbar memindahkan ibu kota Mughal ke Agra dan memulai pembangunan benteng dengan skala yang lebih besar.


Desain dan Struktur: Agra Fort adalah benteng yang mengesankan, terbuat dari batu merah dan dikelilingi oleh tembok tinggi. Benteng ini memiliki dua gerbang utama--Gerbang Delhi (Delhi Gate) dan Gerbang Amar Singh (Amar Singh Gate). Di dalam benteng terdapat berbagai struktur penting seperti istana, masjid, dan aula. Beberapa bangunan terkenal di dalamnya termasuk Khas Mahal (Istana Khusus), Diwan-i-Aam (Aula Umum), dan Diwan-i-Khas (Aula Khusus).


Peran dalam Sejarah Mughal: Agra Fort berfungsi sebagai pusat administratif dan kediaman kekaisaran selama periode Mughal. Benteng ini merupakan lokasi strategis yang mengontrol rute perdagangan penting dan menjadi pusat kekuatan politik.


Pembangunan Lanjutan: Kaisar Shah Jahan, penerus Akbar, juga melakukan sejumlah perluasan dan renovasi di Agra Fort. Dia menambahkan beberapa struktur marmer yang indah, seperti Masjid Moti dan istana-istana mewah. Shah Jahan juga memindahkan ibu kota ke Delhi pada tahun 1648, dan setelah itu, Agra Fort tidak lagi menjadi pusat kekuasaan utama.


Penurunan: Setelah periode Mughal, Agra Fort mengalami penurunan dan beberapa bagian mengalami kerusakan. Benteng ini kemudian jatuh ke tangan penguasa Maratha dan akhirnya ditaklukkan oleh Inggris pada abad ke-19.


Pemeliharaan: Agra Fort diakui sebagai situs Warisan Dunia UNESCO pada tahun 1983 karena nilai sejarah dan arsitekturnya. Pekerjaan restorasi dan pemeliharaan dilakukan untuk menjaga dan melestarikan benteng ini sebagai salah satu monumen penting di India.


Agra Fort adalah contoh yang mencerminkan kekuatan dan kemegahan Dinasti Mughal serta peran strategis yang dimainkannya dalam sejarah India.

name: Nilkamal Chetri
review_text:
Agra Fort is an undeniable masterpiece that transports you to the heart of Mughal India. The sheer scale of the red sandstone fortress is awe-inspiring, and its intricate carvings and architectural brilliance are simply breathtaking.
Stepping inside feels like walking through history. The Diwan-i-Am, the Hall of Public Audience, is a testament to the emperors power, while the Diwan-i-Khas, the Hall of Private Audience, exudes an intimate elegance. The Jahangir Palace, with its delicate marble inlay work, is a feast for the eyes.
While the fort is undoubtedly well-preserved, some areas could benefit from additional restoration. The crowds, especially during peak season, can be overwhelming, but it doesn't detract from the overall experience.
A highlight was undoubtedly the view of the Taj Mahal from the fort walls. Its a perspective that truly captures the essence of both monuments. However, the fort itself, with its rich history and architectural splendor, is the star of the show.
Tip: Allocate ample time to explore the fort. A guided tour can enhance your experience, but its also possible to explore independently. Be sure to wear comfortable shoes as theres a lot of walking involved.
Overall, Agra Fort is a must-visit for anyone interested in history, architecture, or simply experiencing the grandeur of the Mughal era. It's a place that leaves a lasting impression.

name: Piyush Sharma
review_text:
Agra Fort stands tall as a testament to the fact that the Mughals indeed had a lavish lifestyle. The Fort is a gigantic complex built on the River Yamuna and flaunts its beautiful architecture that is inspired from European, Persian, Indian and Islamic Architecture.

The Fort was the imperial residence of the Mughal Empire under the leadership of Mughal Emperor Akbar. \

There are numerous buildings inside the Agra Fort complex such as Diwan-I-Aam (Audience of Common people), Diwan-I-Khas (Audience of special people/nobles of the court), Khas Mahal and more. The upper floors of the Agra Fort offers spectacular Panoramic views of the Taj Mahal.

Agra Fort is easily reachable by road, train and the newly inducted Agra Metro. Opt for Certified tour guides for a better experience.

name: Amit Kale
review_text:
As per online portal Wiki, Agra Fort is a historical fort in the city of Agra in India. It was the main residence of the emperors of the Mughal Dynasty till 1638, when the capital was shifted from Agra to Delhi. The Agra fort is a UNESCO World Heritage site.It is about 2.5 km northwest of its more famous sister monument, the Taj Mahal.

Our personal experience was amazing, though the time of the day and month of the year could have been different. Visitng Agra Fort in mid-day of July is always going to be a challenge with super hot weather. Nevertheless, it has got great history and any proud Maratha would want to go visit this fort where Chaptrapati Shivaji Maharaj was made a prisoner by Mughal Emperor Aurangzeb and the daring escape CSM hatched from there. The gardens and buildings are well maintained. Aim for early morning or late evening visit. Late evening will offer you a perfect glow on TajMahal

name: Ashutosh Toppo (ASHU)
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as Lal Qila, is the second UNESCO World Heritage site in Uttar Pradesh after the Taj Mahal. Constructed by Akbar in 1583, it was added to UNESCOs list of heritage sites in 1983.

The fort is a must-visit destination, boasting architecture and design similar to Delhis Lal Qila, but with a stronger sense of security and heavy guarding during its time.

Within the premises of Agra Fort, visitors can explore Moti Masjid, Diwan-i-khas, Jahangir Palace, Anguri Bagh, Ratan Singh Ki Haveli, Tomb of John Russell Colvin, Shahi Hamam, Machchi Bhawan, Diwan-I-Am, Shish Mahal, Shahi Burj, Shahjahans Marble Throne, and many other fascinating structures.

name: Gaurav Agrawal
review_text:
UNESCO heritage site ,its date of origin is uncertain but very ancient.

Owned by various rulers of Lodhi and Mughals.
Continuously expanded by various rulers.
Served as a capital of Mughal more than once.
Various monuments and palaces inside.
Most of structure was destroyed by britishers.
Rich history associated with this fort.
Please read some history before visiting.
Its architecture is indo-Islamic.
Building built by Shahjahan are mostly of marbles,including the quarters where he was under house arrest for 8-9 years.
A part of fort is occupied by Indian army where tourists are not allowed to.
You can hire a guide here but need to negotiate.
Ticket costs rs 50.
Cloak room is available,bags not allowed inside.
2hrs required to visit the fort.
Wheel chairs and ramps are available here.
Timings :sunrise to sunset.

name: Anil Singh Rathour
review_text: Visiting Agra Fort is an unforgettable experience. This grand fortress, built by Emperor Akbar in the 16th century, is a stunning example of Mughal architecture. As you walk through its massive gates, you're greeted by a blend of red sandstone and white marble structures, each telling a story of the past. The fort's intricate carvings, beautiful palaces like the Jahangir Mahal, and the serene gardens create a sense of awe and wonder. The view of the Taj Mahal from the fort adds to its charm, making it a must-visit for anyone interested in history and architecture.

name: Abhishek Singh
review_text:
I recently visited Agra Fort, and it was an enriching experience. The forts impressive architecture and rich history make it a must-visit destination in Agra.
One of the highlights of my visit was the availability of tour guides who provide insightful details about the forts history, enhancing the overall experience. We opted for an online ticket costing just 45, though offline tickets are also available.
Agra Fort, a UNESCO World Heritage Site, was the main residence of the Mughal emperors until 1638. The fort is a walled city made of red sandstone and includes several beautiful structures like the Jahangir Mahal, Diwan-i-Khas, and the Sheesh Mahal.
Overall, the visit to Agra Fort was fascinating, and I highly recommend it to anyone interested in exploring Indias rich heritage.

name: MUHAMMED SHAFI
review_text:
Agra Fort is a magnificent historical gem that stands as a testament to the grandeur of Mughal architecture. This UNESCO World Heritage site, built in the 16th century, offers visitors a captivating glimpse into Indias rich past.

As you enter through the imposing gates, youre transported to a world of intricate designs and stunning craftsmanship. The forts red sandstone walls hide a complex of palaces, courtyards, and gardens that once served as the seat of Mughal power.

Highlights include the Jahangir Palace, with its blend of Hindu and Islamic styles, and the Khas Mahal, showcasing exquisite marble work. The Diwan-i-Khas, where emperors held private audiences, is a marvel of design with its ornate pillars and inlaid stones.

Dont miss the Musamman Burj, a tower offering breathtaking views of the Taj Mahal in the distance. The forts strategic location along the Yamuna River adds to its picturesque setting.

While exploring, youll encounter knowledgeable guides eager to share fascinating historical anecdotes. The forts vast expanse means comfortable walking shoes are a must.

Visit early morning or late afternoon to avoid the heat and crowds. Allow at least 2-3 hours to fully appreciate this architectural wonder.

Agra Fort is a must-visit for history buffs, architecture enthusiasts, and anyone seeking to immerse themselves in the opulence of Mughal India.

name: Aviral Gupta
review_text:
Agra fort is located in Agra city of Rajasthan. It was built by Mughal Emperor Jalaluddin Mohammad Akbar. It is the most beautiful fort I ever seen. Also it covers very large area. I have visited this fort on my last vacation. It was a great experience and when the guide tells us about the fort how it is made, history of it, water facilities, fountains, and about the importance of architecture, etc.

The outer walls is made up of red stones and inside the fort we can see best combination of Sang e marmar and red stones. There was Diwaan-e-khaas for special people and Diwaan-e-aam for local people.

We can easily see Taj Mahal from the terrace of this fort. Also there was a Takht-e-Jahangir ( Throne of Jahangir) made up of black Stone imported from Belgium by Jahangir. Behind the Takht-e-Jahangir a chain is present consists of 60 metal bells called Nyaya ki Janjeer ( Chain of Truth) .

name: Rashmita Panigrahi
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort of Agra, is a historic fortification located in the city of Agra, India. Built by Emperor Akbar in 1573, this massive red sandstone structure served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors until the capital was moved to Delhi. Spanning approximately 94 acres, the fort is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and an exemplary representation of Mughal architecture. The forts intricate design features a blend of Hindu and Islamic architectural styles, showcasing detailed carvings, ornate palaces, and beautiful gardens. The Agra Fort not only offers a glimpse into Indias rich history but also provides stunning views of the nearby Taj Mahal, adding to its historical and aesthetic significance.

When visiting Agra Fort, consider the following tips for an enriching experience:

1. Timing- The fort is open daily from sunrise to sunset, typically from 6:00 AM to 6:00 PM. Arrive early to avoid crowds and the midday heat.

2. Tickets- Purchase your tickets at the entrance. There are separate pricing for Indian citizens and foreign tourists. You can also buy tickets online to save time.
For Indian Citizen, price is - Rs 50/ person

3. Guides-Hire a local guide for an informative tour. Official guides can provide detailed historical context and interesting anecdotes about the fort's history and architecture. Guide fees- Rs 200 - Rs 600

4. Entry Points- The main entrance is the Amar Singh Gate, which is the only gate open to visitors. It leads directly into the fort's main complex.

5. Highlights- Don't miss key attractions within the fort, such as the Jahangir Mahal, Diwan-i-Aam, Diwan-i-Khas, Khas Mahal, and the Musamman Burj. Each structure has unique historical significance and architectural beauty.

6. Photography- Photography is allowed, so bring your camera to capture the intricate details and panoramic views, especially the distant Taj Mahal visible from certain points within the fort.

7. Dress Comfortably- Wear comfortable shoes and light clothing, as you will be doing a fair amount of walking. Carry water, especially during hot months.

8. Security- There are security checks at the entrance. Avoid carrying large bags or prohibited items to speed up the process.

9. Accessibility- Some areas of the fort may not be wheelchair accessible due to steps and uneven paths. Plan accordingly if you have mobility issues.

10. Nearby Attractions- Combine your visit with other nearby attractions like the Taj Mahal and Fatehpur Sikri for a comprehensive tour of Agras historical sites.

review_text:
Agra Fort, a UNESCO World Heritage site, is a stunning example of Mughal architecture and history. Built primarily from red sandstone, this 16th-century fortification was commissioned by Emperor Akbar and later modified by his successors. The fort houses several exquisite buildings, including the Jahangir Mahal, Khas Mahal, Diwan-i-Khas, and the iconic Moti Masjid. Its intricate carvings, grand halls, and beautiful gardens reflect the opulence and grandeur of the Mughal era. Overlooking the Yamuna River, Agra Fort offers breathtaking views of the nearby Taj Mahal, making it a must-visit for history enthusiasts and tourists alike.

name: Priti Pandey
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as Lal Quila (Red Fort), is a majestic Mughal monument boasting a rich history and stunning architecture. It served as the main residence of Mughal emperors for nearly a century and offers a glimpse into their opulent lifestyle.
Heres what makes Lal Quila a must-visit:
* Imposing Red Fortress: The forts red sandstone walls, adorned with intricate carvings, are a sight to behold. Explore the ramparts for panoramic views of the city.
* Architectural Marvels: Wander through the grand palaces, including Jahangir Mahal and Khas Mahal, and marvel at the beautiful pietra dura inlay work. Dont miss the audience halls, mosques, and the iconic Diwan-e- aam (Hall of Public Audience).
* Riverside Location: The forts location along the Yamuna River adds to its charm. Enjoy the scenic vistas, especially during sunset.
Tips for your visit:
* Purchase tickets online to avoid queues.
* Consider hiring a guide for a more enriching experience.
* Carry comfortable shoes for walking, as the fort complex is vast.
* Bring water and snacks, as options inside the fort are limited.

The smell of rats and moles is a negative point here.

name: sadarulla khan
review_text:
Agra Fort is a historic fort in the city of Agra, India. It served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors until 1638, when the capital was shifted from Agra to Delhi. Here are some key points about Agra Fort:

Location:
Situated on the right bank of the Yamuna River.

History:
Originally built as a brick fort by the Rajput kings, it was extensively renovated and rebuilt in red sandstone by Emperor Akbar in 1573.

Architecture:
The fort is a UNESCO World Heritage site, showcasing a mix of Hindu and Islamic architecture. Significant buildings within the fort include the Jahangir Mahal, Khas Mahal, Diwan-i-Khas, Diwan-i-Am, and the Musamman Burj.

Significance:
It played a vital role in the history of the Mughal Empire, serving both as a military stronghold and a royal residence.

Tourism:
Today, it is a popular tourist destination, attracting visitors for its historical importance and architectural beauty.

name: Kabeer M
review_text:
Massive walled city built at the peak of Mughal power. As with all monuments and historical sites inside Agra, one should be wary of commission-hungry tourists guides. I'd suggest only getting a certified tour guide near the gate. The whole tour takes about 2-3 hours, and covers a lot of history and beautiful architecture. The layout is D-shaped, but tourists can only enter the Amar Singh Gate as a large part of the fort is used by the Indian Army. Overall, a beautiful and stunning expanse of architecture with variety, but I wish the government would care for it too, rather than just focusing on the Taj Mahal...

review_text:
Well mai jab yahan aaaya tha tab sirf 40% hi tourists ke liye allowed tha 60% was not allowed to explore due to reasons like construction, privacy, legalities, danger etc mai pagal tha jo Taj Mahal dekh kr ye dekhne aya tha Bhai ye 40% ke liye bhi tumko pura din Dena padega warna thak ke mere jaisa haal ho jayega; aur most imp yaha 5 litre Pani sath leke chalna meri vaat lag gayi thi Pani ke chakkar me.

Well fort ke baare tarif jeetni bhi kare Kam hi padegi so ye sab chhodke info dekho 

The Agra Fort (Qila Agra) is a historical fort in the city of Agra, and also known as Agras Red Fort. Mughal emperor Humayun was crowned at this fort in 1530. It was later renovated by the Mughal emperor Akbar from 1565 and the present-day structure was completed in 1573. It served as the main residence of the rulers of the Mughal dynasty until 1638, when the capital was shifted from Agra to Delhi. It was also known as the Lal-Qila or Qila-i-Akbari.[1] Before being captured by the British, the last Indian rulers to have occupied it were the Marathas. In 1983, the Agra fort was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site because of its importance during the Mughal Dynasty.[2] It is about 2.5 kilometers (1.6 mi) northwest of its more famous sister monument, the Taj Mahal. The fort can be more accurately described as a walled city. It was later renovated by Shah Jahan.

name: Vishal Ch
review_text:
Wandering through the Majestic Agra Fort, a stunning example of Mughal architecture that reflects Indias rich history. The massive red sandstone walls  and intricate carvings on every surface tell stories of a grand past.
.
From the towering Amar Singh Gate to the detailed artistry on the walls, the blend of Islamic, Persian, and Indian styles creates a visual feast.
.
As a photographer , capturing these timeless details feels like stepping back into history, showcasing the forts grandeur and intricate beauty.
.

In Agra's embrace, a fortress stands high,
A canvas of history beneath the vast sky.
Red walls and carvings, tales etched in stone,
Whispers of an era, in every groove shown.

name: Abinash
review_text:
Agra Fort is located on the Yamuna River in the city of Agra in west-central Uttar Pradesh, India
- Other names: Agra Fort is also known as the Red Fort
- Establishment: Agra Fort was established by Mughal emperor Akbar
- Architecture: Agra Fort is made entirely of red sandstone
- Timing: The timings of the fort are from sunrise to sunset
- Entry Fee: The entry fee for Indians is INR 40 and for foreigners is INR 550
- Time Required: It takes 2-3 hours to visit the fort
- UNESCO World Heritage site: The fort was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983
- Historical significance: It is the perfect example of Mughal art and architecture

name: ABHISHEK KAPOOR
review_text: Agra Fort isnt just a majestic red sandstone monument; its a captivating journey through Mughal history. Commissioned by Emperor Akbar the Great in the mid-16th century, the fort served as both a military base and a royal residence for generations of Mughal emperors. Imagine towering walls, intricate carvings, and opulent palaces whispering tales of emperors like Jahangir and Shah Jahan (who, ironically, was imprisoned here by his own son!). Within the forts embrace lies the exquisite Pearl Mosque, a testament to Mughal artistry, and Jahangirs private quarters, offering a glimpse into royal life. Agra Fort isnt just a structure; its a captivating historical experience, transporting you back to an era of opulence and power.

name: A v k technical guru (Peengri)
review_text:
**Red Fort of Agra - a symbol of Mughal pride and power**

The Red Fort of Agra, also known as Agra Fort, is located on the banks of the Yamuna River in Uttar Pradesh. It is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and is located at a distance of about 2.5 kilometers from the Taj Mahal. The construction of this fort was started by the Mughal emperor Akbar in the 16th century, and was later completed by Shahjahan.

The Red Fort is made of red sandstone, and its walls are approximately 2.5 kilometers long. There are many important buildings within it which reflect the excellence of Mughal architecture. Diwan-e-Aam (Public Assembly Hall) and Diwan-e-Khas (Private Assembly Hall) are the main attractions here. Diwan-i-Khas is the place where Emperor Shah Jahan spent his last years as a prisoner, and from here he could see the Taj Mahal.

Other major sites of the fort include the Shahi Mosque, Khas Mahal, Angoori Bagh, and Jahangir Mahal. The Shahi Mosque is made of white marble and its beauty is unique. Angoori Bagh is a magnificent example of Mughal horticultural art, where grape vines and other fruit trees were planted.

The Red Fort is not just a fort; It is a symbol of the power, glory and cultural richness of the Mughal rule. The architecture here is a blend of Mughal, Persian, Turkish and Indian styles, which makes it architecturally unique.

The Red Fort of Agra is famous not only for its architecture but also for its important role in Indian history. This is the place where many important events of the Mughal Empire took place. While visiting this fort, tourists can feel the depth of Mughal history, art, and culture.

Visiting the Red Fort is an unforgettable experience for history lovers and art lovers. This place reminds us of the greatness of Indian history and the rich heritage of the Mughal period. The Red Fort of Agra, together with the Taj Mahal, makes Agra one of the most important tourist destinations in India.

Weekend

name: Harsh & Leena Bansal
review_text:
Agra fort is too big and it takes extra efforts to cover the whole without taking a break and it is 2.5 km.
I would suggest getting a guide to cover the impotence of all the places in fort.
The Agra Fort, also known as the "Lal -Qila", "Fort Rouge" or "Qila-i-Akbari", is the highlight of the city of Agra, then capital of the Mughal Sultanate .
Mughal emperor Humayun was crowned at this fort in 1530.
It was later renovated by the Mughal emperor Akbar from 1565 and the present-day structure was completed in 1573.
Located close to River Yamuna is the magnificent Agra Fort.

Magnificent Structures Inside Agra Fort
1. Jehangir Mahal
2. Khas Mahal
3. Musamman Burj
4. Sheesh Mahal
5. Diwan - I- Khaas
6. Diwan - E - Am
7. Nagina Masjid
8. Moti Masjid

Ticketing
1. Foreign Tourist Rs. 650/- Friday - Rs. 600/-
2. Domestic/Indian Tourist Rs. 50/- Friday - Rs. 40/-

Day Timing

Tuesday 6:00 am - 6:00 pm

name: Nitin Kumar
review_text:
Incredible Experience at Agra Fort!

My recent visit to Agra Fort was an unforgettable experience. This UNESCO World Heritage Site is a must-visit for history enthusiasts and architecture lovers. The forts magnificent red sandstone walls, intricate carvings, and expansive courtyards transport you back to the Mughal era. Highlights include the Diwan-i-Am (Hall of Public Audience), the Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience), and the stunning Musamman Burj with its view of the Taj Mahal. The well-maintained gardens and informative plaques make exploring the fort both enjoyable and educational. Agra Fort is easily accessible and a perfect addition to your Agra itinerary. Highly recommend!

name: rajesh jaiswar
review_text:
The Agra Fort or Red Fort, as it is popularly referred to, is one of the most historically significant sites in the whole of India. The Fort is a gargantuan walled city that has seen several dynasties ruling and getting overthrown over the course of numerous centuries. It was the chief abode of the emperors of Mughal Dynasty and has been witness to the crowning of Humayun. The Fort attained its present form under Akbar who made it his capital and ruled from the majestic site. The glorious fort is extremely important and enjoys a proud position in the UNESCO World Heritage sites list.

History of Agra Fort
The fort, way different from its present glorious form, is believed to have been built by the Rajput King Raja Badal Singh and was initially known as Badalgarh. After the First Battle of Panipat, the Mughals stayed in the Fort and made it their official residence. In 1558, Akbar made Agra his capital city and reigned over his subjects from the Agra Fort. It was during Akbar's time that the Fort was transformed completely. A total of 4000 workers took to the task of renovating the Fort for a period of 8 long years. Rebuilding the Fort with red sandstone, Akbar transformed the very site and it acquired the name of Lal Quila or Red Fort which is how it is referred to till date.

Architecture of Agra Fort
The Red Fort is a striking masterpiece of Islamic Architecture. The massive fort stretches for a total of 2.5 kilometres and its exterior is made of stunning red sandstone while the interior constitutes of bricks. The enormous walls of this fort are 70 feet in height and add to its charm. While the fort has 4 gates, one on each side, only two of these gates are prominent. The Lahori Gate which is also known as Amar Singh Gate is the main entrance for visitors whereas the Delhi Gate was used by Akbar as his entrance and is known for its gorgeous Indo-Islamic architecture. Inside the Fort lie momentous structures like Jahangir's Hauz, Shahjahani Mahal, Babur's Baoli, Nagina Masjid, Akbar's Mahal, Diwan-e-Aam, to name a few, which are important components of our heritage.

name: CR SIYAG
review_text:
Agra Fort is a huge fort situated on the banks of Yamuna River in Agra, Uttar Pradesh which is famous all over the world. This fort is only 2.5 kilometers away from Taj Mahal. Agra Fort was the site of a battle during the Indian Rebellion of 1857. The Marathas attacked Agra Fort in the early 18th century and the ownership of the fort changed several times.

Sikandar Lodi was the first Sultan of Delhi who shifted his capital from Delhi to Agra which was known as Badalgarh for 9 years until his defeat in the First Battle of Panipat. When Babur sent his son Humayun to Agra, he captured the Badal Garh fort and seized a vast treasure including the famous Kohinoor diamond.

When Akbar reached Agra in 1558, he realized the importance of the city and made Agra his capital. Shahjahan was the grandson of Akbar and he destroyed some of the buildings of the fort to make way for himself which Agra Fort still represents today.

Talking about the famous buildings inside Agra Fort, let us tell you that there are Jahangir Mahal, Khas Mahal, Musamman Burj, Sheesh Mahal, Nagina Masjid, Moti Masjid etc. Humayun was crowned king in 1530. After Humayuns defeat to Sher Shah Suri, the Mughals again lost the fort.

jb akbr ne 1558 meN aagraa phuNce to unhoNne shhr ke mhtv ko mhsuus kie aur aagraa ko apnii raajdhaanii bnaa lie /  shaahjhaaN akbr kaa potaa thaa usne apnii jgh bnaane ke lie kile kii kuch imaartoN ko nsstt kr diyaa jo aaj bhii aagraa kile ko prstut krtaa hai / 


aagraa kile ke aNdr prsiddh imaarteN kii baat kreN to hm aapko btaa deN ki jhaaNgiir mhl, khaas mhl, musmmn burj, shiish mhl, ngiinaa msjid, motii msjid aadi hai /  1530 meN humaayuuN kaa raaj abhissek huaa shershaah suurii ko humaayuuN ke haar ke baad mugloN ne phir se kile ko kho diyaa /

name: ANJALI WADHWA
review_text:
Thoroughly enjoyed each and every second of this splendid location. Truly all the Mughal history is visible in agra fort. The numerous rooms and airy courtyards. Diwan-e-aam as well as diwan-e-khas. Two magnificent thrones placed at separate locations. The rooms in which the females would have lived at that time. The masjid inside the fort. Lovely location of agra fort as at one point we can see the taj mahal from agra fort. Not only at one point but from various different angles and different rooms it is visible. A very good place for some nice photography session. Rich in history. Some areas are blocked and not allowed entrance into but you can still see it through the gates and it gives a feel about how they used to live there. You can see the place where shah jahan used to come and give public appearance at that time. The big entrance hate to the agra fort. Spacious. Minimal fee for ticket and maximum fun. Better to go on a rainy or monsoon day. It is a bit tiring when you visit on a sunny day.

name: Jaideep Rahar
review_text:
The Agra fort is a UNESCO World Heritage site.It is about 2.5 km northwest of its more famous sister monument, the Taj Mahal. The fort can be more accurately described as a walled city. After the First Battle of Panipat in 1526, the victorious Babur stayed in the fort, in the palace of Ibrahim LodiAgra Fort is a good place to visit of history and architecture interests you. We opted for a guide from our hotel which we now realise we should have taken one directly at the fort as the charge was almost double. However if one is not interested in knowing the history of the place, a visit without guide would do. About 20% of fort is open to public rest is under army control per our guide and this 20% itself took us about 30 to 45 mins. Entrance ticket of Rs 50 for Indians, cameras and phones are allowed. Fort closes at 5 or 5.30 in the evening. Be careful of pickpockets and people trying to sell or force you to buy things when stepping out. Grand architecture and well maintained fort..

name: Akash
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site in Agra, India. This magnificent fort was built by Mughal Emperor Akbar in 1565 and served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors for nearly 200 years. The fort is constructed using red sandstone and has an impressive area of around 94 acres.

The architectural design of Agra Fort is a blend of Persian, Turkish, and Indian styles. It features high walls with bastions at regular intervals, with two main entrances: the Amar Singh Gate on the eastern side and the Lahori Gate on the western side. As visitors enter through the Amar Singh Gate, they are greeted by a large courtyard known as the Diwan-i-Aam or Hall of Public Audience.

The fort houses several significant structures within its premises, including:

1. Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience): This hall is adorned with intricate carvings and inlay work featuring semi-precious stones. It was used for private meetings between the emperor and his courtiers.

2. Sheesh Mahal (Palace of Mirrors): This stunning palace is covered in mirror work and offers breathtaking views of the surrounding gardens.

3. Moti Masjid (Pearl Mosque): Built by Emperor Aurangzeb in 1653, this beautiful mosque is constructed using white marble and features elegant arches and domes.

4. Khas Mahal (Private Palace): This palace was used by Emperor Shah Jahan as his private residence during his stay at Agra Fort.

5. Anguri Bagh (Grape Garden): This beautiful garden offers an enchanting view of Taj Mahal from across Yamuna River.

Agra Fort showcases a rich history of Mughal architecture and serves as a testament to Indias cultural heritage. With its well-preserved structures, it attracts millions of tourists every year who come to marvel at its grandeur and beauty.

review_text:
The fort that once was the stronghold of the Mughal empire now rests calm as the tourist engulf it in their footsteps . This fort was originally built by lodhi dynasty then reformed by Emperor Babur , Emperor Humayun and made stronger,powerful and prominent by Emperor Akbur . The fort contains rich history and architecture. It captures a breathtaking view of the taj mahal . It consists of Diwan e khas ,Diwan e aam , sheesh mahal , and many more important historical monuments. Its a dream place for history lovers .

name: Paul C.
review_text:
A very big fort with intricate details on the walls and structures of the fort, with its red sand stone facade and elaborate interiors that shows how architecture was used to cool the inhabitants of the fort. The fort also has a rich history as well. Today, the Indian Army occupies most of the fort. You can even see the Taj Mahal from here as well.

Visited in May 2024.

name: P
review_text:
Monumental Royal Fortress

Often named in the same breath as the Taj Mahal, this landmark structure is fortified by 21-meter (70-feet) high walls, part of which skirts the river Yamuna.

The Agra Fort gained prominence during the reign of Emperor Akbar and Shah Jahan. The forts complex gives a great view of the majestic Jahangiri Mahal, dwarfing everything else surrounding the palace.

The smooth contours of the Taj Mahal are hard to be missed from the Khas Mahal and Musamman Burj, that is only if you can take your eyes off the splendid polished color stones and gems that beautify the structures. Diwan-i-Khas, Diwan-i- Aam, Anguri Bagh and Machhi Bhavan are other historically important structures that are also the holders of the Mughal legacy.

If the white marble wonder is the royal symbol of an emperors love for his wife, then the Agra Fort surely lives up to its status of a royal fortress. Built in such gigantic proportions, it is practically impossible to capture the fort in a frame from any one side.

Open : Sunrise to sunset.

Distance about: 5.5 Kms from Agra Cantt Railway Station.

Entry fee at Agra Fort

1. Foreign Tourist Rs. 650/-
Friday - Rs. 600/-

2. Domestic/Indian Tourist Rs. 50/- Friday - Rs. 40/-

Note-
Please keep your ID with you.
No Entry fee for children below the age of 15 years.

name: Amy Lin
review_text:
[Agra Fort] Agra Fort straddles the Yamana River. This castle was built by Emperor Akbar in 1565. It has the dual functions of a palace and a castle. Most of the buildings in the city are made of It is built of red sandstone, so it is called the Red Fort. This fortress is surrounded by a moat and a spectacular city wall that is 2.5 kilometers long and more than 20 meters high, making it appear sacred and inviolable. The castle guards beautiful palaces including Jahanj Palace, Hasmahal Palace, etc. The beautiful halls, rich and diverse stone carvings, exquisite beams and pillars are worth seeing. It is said that King Shah Jahan was imprisoned in the octagonal tower in this fort by his three sons in his later years, and he stared at the tomb of his beloved wife every day until his death.

name: Mohtamim's vision of CNCP
review_text:
An architectural heritage with lots of memories.
The Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort, has a rich history that dates back to the 11th century. The fort was originally built as a military fortification along the Yamuna River to protect the city of Agra from attacks by rival kingdoms. During the reign of Emperor Akbar (1556-1605), the fort was expanded and transformed into a grand royal residence. It served as the main residence of the Mughal dynasty until 1638, when the capital was moved from Agra to Delhi

name: Portugueses em Viagem
review_text:
Discover the grandeur of Agra Fort, an architectural wonder located on the banks of the Yamuna River, in India. Built in the 16th century by Emperor Akbar, this magnificent fort is a testament to the wealth and power of the Mughal Empire. As you enter its imposing gates, you are enveloped by the atmosphere of grandeur and history that permeates every stone.

The beauty of Agra Fort is evident in every detail. From the elaborate palaces to the intricate gardens, each element reflects the expertise of the artisans of the time. As you explore its courtyards and halls, you will be captivated by the opulence of the frescoes and the delicacy of the details, which testify to the splendor of the past.

The views from Agra Fort are truly stunning. From the top of its walls, you can contemplate the majestic Taj Mahal, which rises in the distance like an architectural masterpiece. The Yamuna River gently meanders around the fort, creating a scene of serenity that contrasts with its grandeur.

The history of Agra Fort is as fascinating as its architecture. Over the centuries, it has been the scene of events that shaped Indias destiny, from epic battles to the rise and fall of empires. Each room and passage tells a part of that story, and as you walk through its corridors, you feel transported to the heart of the past.

Be sure to include Agra Fort in your itinerary when you visit India. This masterpiece of Mughal architecture awaits you, ready to enchant you with its beauty and captivate you with its history. A visit to this historical treasure is an experience that will remain etched in your memory forever.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
No
review_translated_text:
Descobre a grandiosidade do Forte de Agra, uma maravilha arquitetonica situada nas margens do rio Yamuna, na India. Construido no seculo XVI pelo imperador Akbar, este magnifico forte e um testemunho da riqueza e poder do Imperio Mughal. Ao adentrares os seus portoes imponentes, es envolvido pela atmosfera de grandeza e historia que permeia cada pedra.


A beleza do Forte de Agra e evidente em cada detalhe. Desde os elaborados palacios ate aos intrincados jardins, cada elemento reflete a pericia dos artesaos da epoca. A medida que exploras os seus patios e saloes, es cativado pela opulencia dos afrescos e pela delicadeza dos detalhes, que testemunham o esplendor do passado.


As vistas do Forte de Agra sao verdadeiramente deslumbrantes. Do alto das suas muralhas, contemplas o majestoso Taj Mahal, que se ergue ao longe como uma obra-prima da arquitetura. O rio Yamuna serpenteia suavemente ao redor do forte, criando um cenario de serenidade que contrasta com a sua imponencia.


A historia do Forte de Agra e tao fascinante quanto a sua arquitetura. Ao longo dos seculos, foi palco de eventos que moldaram o destino da India, desde batalhas epicas ate a ascensao e queda de imperios. Cada sala e passagem conta uma parte dessa historia, e ao percorreres os seus corredores, sentes-te transportado para o coracao do passado.


Nao deixes de incluir o Forte de Agra no teu roteiro quando visitares a India. Esta obra-prima da arquitetura mogol espera por ti, pronta para te encantar com a sua beleza e te cativar com a sua historia. Uma visita a este tesouro historico e uma experiencia que ficara gravada na tua memoria para sempre.

name: Carlos Gamuci Millan
review_text:
Precious. Having the Taj Majal in Agra, no one pays attention to its fort (although it is more of a fortified palace), which is evident in the fact that it has much less traffic, but it is worth seeing. I recommend that, as soon as you go up the access hill, you turn right to see the old part first and thus end up in the beautiful courtyard of the public audiences of the new part. There is a room where any whisper in a corner facing the wall is perfectly heard in the opposite corner. I hope you find it. You have to hear it to believe it!
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
Not sure
review_translated_text: Precioso. Teniendo el Taj Majal en Agra nadie se fija en su fuerte (aunque mas bien es un palacio fortificado), lo que se nota en que tiene mucha menos afluencia, pero es digno de ver. Recomiendo que, nada mas subir la cuesta del acceso gireis a la derecha para ver primero la parte vieja y asi terminar en el precioso patio de las audiencias publicas de la parte nueva. Hay una sala en donde cualquier susurro en una esquina de cara a la pared se escucha perfectamente en la esquina opuesta. Espero que la encontreis. !Hay que oirlo para creerlo!

name: Nguyen Thi Thanh Loan
review_text:
AGRA RED FORT, beautiful and vast. It is called the Red Fort because it is built mostly of red sandstone, with white marble in some places.
The fortress was built in the 16th century.
The Forts architecture is a combination of Persian and Islamic architecture.
Agra port is a historical monument of India and was honored by UNESCO as a cultural heritage site.

name: Prabhat Kumar
review_text:
Visiting Agra Fort was an unforgettable experience that transported me to a bygone era of grandeur and opulence. From the moment I stepped through its imposing gates, I was captivated by the sheer magnificence of the forts architecture. The intricately carved marble panels, delicate lattice work, and towering minarets spoke volumes about the craftsmanship of the Mughal artisans.

As I wandered through the labyrinthine passages and expansive courtyards, I couldnt help but marvel at the rich history that permeated every stone of the fort. Each section seemed to have a story to tell, from the elegant Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience) to the formidable Jahangir Mahal.

One of the highlights of my visit was the breathtaking view of the Taj Mahal from the forts ramparts. Seeing the iconic monument shimmering in the distance against the backdrop of the Yamuna River was a moment Ill cherish forever.

Overall, my time at Agra Fort left me with a deep appreciation for Indias cultural heritage and a desire to delve even further into its fascinating history. Its truly a must-visit destination for anyone traveling to the region.

Weekend

name: Debashis Guha Thakurta
review_text:
Emperor Shahjahan spent his last years here in captivity. Helpful plaques are there within the fort, but you would enjoy the place better with little history homework on your end. Guides are available within 200-400/- (depending on your bargaining skills), but not reliable. Not so crowded like Taj Mahal, but historically quite a significant.

name: Silvana Guerra
review_text:
Simply extraordinary, a fortification and a palace at the same time, which is a world heritage site. The complex has several buildings inside, the most important and spectacular is the emperors private palace, with a large garden attached. The harmony of the decorated and inlaid marble and the play of the red sandstone of the surrounding buildings are extraordinary. A visit absolutely not to be missed, a few km from the Taj Mahal.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
Not sure
review_translated_text: Semplicemente straordinario, una fortificazione e un palazzo allo stesso tempo, che e patrimonio dell umanita. Il complesso ha al suo interno diversi edifici, il piu importante e spettacolare e il palazzo privato dell imperatore, con annesso un grande giardino. L armonia dei marmi decorati e intarsiati e il gioco dell arenaria rossa degli edifici circostanti, sono straordinari. Una visita assolutamente da non perdere, a pochi km dal Taj Mahal.

name: Steven FAN
review_text: Agra Fort: Very similar to the Red Fort in the capital Delhi, mostly built with red sandstone, but more complete and majestic than it, and more interesting to watch. Construction began with the fourth generation monarch of the Mughal Empire, and each building complex is full of the personal style of the king who built it at that time. There are historical stories in the Indian version of palace drama.

name: Rajinder vishwkarma
review_text:
Among the major attractions in the fort is Jahangir's Palace (Jahangiri Mahal), built by Akbar as a private palace for his son Jahangir. It is the largest residence in the complex. The Pearl Mosque (Moti Masjid), constructed by Shah Jahan, is a tranquil and perfectly proportioned structure made entirely of white marble. The Hall of Private Audience (Diwan-i-Khas) was used for receiving distinguished visitors. The famous Peacock Throne was once kept there, before Aurangzeb took it to Delhi.....

name: Aowlad Hossain
review_text:
A Majestic Mughal Marvel: Agra Fort Review

Agra Fort is an awe-inspiring monument that shouldnt be missed on any trip to Agra. Heres what makes it a must-see:

Rich History: Built in the 16th century by Mughal emperors, the fort offers a glimpse into Indias rich historical tapestry. Explore the intricate carvings and architecture that tell the story of a bygone era.
Architectural Grandeur: The red sandstone fort is a masterpiece of Mughal architecture. Be amazed by the imposing walls, magnificent gates like the Delhi Gate, and the delicate details on the buildings within the complex.
Unforgettable Views: The fort offers stunning panoramic views of the Taj Mahal across the Yamuna River. Capture breathtaking photos and appreciate the scale and proximity of these two iconic monuments.

Additional Tips:

Purchase Tickets Online: Avoid long queues by purchasing your entry tickets online beforehand.
Hire a Guide: Consider hiring a knowledgeable guide to get in-depth insights into the forts history and significance.
Explore the Various Sites: Dont miss the Jahangir Mahal palace, the Diwan-i-Am (Hall of Public Audience), and the impressive Machchi Bhawan (fish market) within the fort complex.

Overall, Agra Fort is a historical treasure that deserves a dedicated visit. Its architectural beauty, rich history, and stunning views will leave you spellbound.

Weekday

name: Dmitry Borodin
review_text:
Probably, if you have already arrived in Agra, then you need to visit, but we were here after the Taj Mahal and Amber Fort in Jaipur, so the impressions were very modest. The fort is small (compared to Amber Fort), we walked around all the accessible places in just 30 minutes. Crowds of people that fill the entire space and make it impossible to take photographs without people. Part of the fort (I felt like the most interesting) was closed to the public... Tickets are sold only in cash, you cannot pay by card, and for some reason online purchases did not work on the website...
Visited on
Weekday

Up to 10 min

Reservation recommended
Yes
review_translated_text: Navernoe, esli uzhe priehali v Agru, to posetit nuzhno, no my zdes byli uzhe posle Tadzh-Mahala i Amber-forta v Dzhaypure, poetomu vpechatleniya byli vesma skromnymi. Fort nebolshoy (po sravneniyu s Amber-fortom), my oboshli vse dostupnye dlya poseshcheniya mesta bukvalno za 30 minut. Tolpy narodu, kotorye zapolnyayut vse prostranstvo, i delayut nevozmozhnym fotografii bez lyudey. Chast forta (po oshchushcheniyam , samaya interesnaya) byla zakryta dlya poseshcheniya... Bilety prodayutsya tolko za nalichnye, kartoy oplatit nelzya, a pokupka v internete pochemu-to na sayte ne prohodila...

name: Akash Harbala
review_text:
Agra Fort - A Majestic Citadel

Exploring Agra Fort was a journey through history that Ill never forget. The forts imposing red sandstone walls and intricate architecture are truly impressive, offering a glimpse into Indias rich past.

Walking through its grand gates and expansive courtyards, I was struck by the sheer scale of the fort and the stories it holds within its walls. From the opulent palaces to the strategic military defenses, every corner of Agra Fort tells a tale of power, intrigue, and resilience.

The views of the Taj Mahal from within the fort are breathtaking, providing a unique perspective on this iconic landmark. Whether youre a history buff or simply looking to immerse yourself in Indias cultural heritage, a visit to Agra Fort is a must.

Many parts of the fort are closed for visiting but still the fort is so huge that you will be lost in it ..
Visited on
Weekend

Up to 10 min

Reservation recommended
No

review_text:

name: Istekar Ali
review_text: This massive red sandstone fort was built on the banks of the Yamuna River in 1565 by Akbar, the first Mughal emperor in India. Further improvements were made by his successors; Shah Jahan built the impressive imperial quarters and mosque, while Aurangzeb added the outer ramparts. The fort was built primarily as a military structure, but Shah Jahan transformed it into a palace, and later it became his gilded prison for eight years after his son Aurangzeb seized power in 1658.

name: Ketan Desai
review_text:
Agra Fort is a must destination for anyone traveling to Agra. From the impressive entrance gate to the beautiful palaces and gardens inside, Agra Fort is a sight to behold. It also offers a breathtaking view of the iconic Taj Mahal, making it a popular spot for tourists.

Beware of the scams going on around this tourist places. Guides are charging tremendously for little information. Auto rikshwalas almost forcing you to take auto everywhere but rather go for ola or Uber.

Auto wala offered me 600 rs but when I booked ola/Uber to all the places I wanted to visit in Agra and I managed to get this around 350 rs.

So do your research and take decisions accordingly.

name: PAPPOO
review_text:
Agra Fort is located in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh and is an important part of Indian history. It was built by Akbar in the 16th century and is situated on the hills of Akhbarpur. The fort is characterized by its stylistic architecture, magnificent structure, and historical importance.

Delhi Gate, the main gate of Agra Fort, reflects the grandeur of the Indian military history. Its walls are high and strong, showing unmatched defense over the centuries. There are many places inside the fort such as Moti Masjid, Diwan-e-Aam, and Diwan-e-Khas.

Agra Fort is located next to the Taj Mahal, due to which it is famous all over the world. Both these places are a symbol of Akbars pride and are one of the most important symbols of Indian culture.

Agra Fort is not only an important part of Indian history, but it is also a unique tourist destination that attracts tourists from all over the country.

name: DIMPLE KUMARI
review_text:
Located close to River Yamuna is the magnificent Agra Fort. It offers a captivating glimpse into the royal lifestyle and architectural brilliance of the Mughal Empire. It's one of the most popular historical tourist places of Agra. Here, you'll find yourself immersed in the grandeur of Mughal architecture.

Explore the various halls like Diwan-e-Aam and Diwan-e-Khaas, and the palaces like Jahangir Palace and Khaas Mahal. Savour the moment of tranquillity and respite they offer. The high, red sandstone walls surround you completely. You'll forget you're in 21st-century Agra.
No tour to Agra is ever complete without visiting the Agra Fort.

name: Nishant Chauhan
review_text:
The building is massive, very likely it was built in place of the old Badalgarh Fort, stronghold of Rajput rulers. Surrounded by a double wall, of which the outer one is 40 ft high and the inner one 70 ft, the fort was started in 1565 and completed in eight years, matching the different tastes of each of the Mughal kings that contributed in its creation.One of the greatest buildings is the red-sand-stone Jahangir's Palace, built by Akbar the Great. History here is a little confused, the palace is believed to have been built by the king for his son, then later emperor Jahangir built another palace after demolishing one of the areas that Akbar had devoted to his Hindu wife Jodha Bai.

In summary, a visit to the Agra Fort is not only a journey through time but also an opportunity to marvel at the architectural prowess and historical significance of one of Indias most iconic monuments.
