name: Sanni Gupta
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort, is a historic fort located in the city of Agra in the Indian state of Uttar Pradesh. It is situated on the banks of the Yamuna River and is about 2.5 kilometers north-west of the Taj Mahal.

The history of Agra Fort dates back to the 11th century. It was originally a brick fort, which was renovated by Sikandar Lodi (1487-1517) in 1504. After the victory in the First Battle of Panipat (1526),   the Mughal emperor Babur captured Agra Fort and made it his capital.

After Babur, his successor Humayun made many changes in the Agra Fort. He constructed many buildings in the fort, including Sher Mandal, Angoori Bagh and Moti Masjid.

After Humayun, his son Akbar made Agra Fort more grand. He constructed many new buildings in the fort, including Diwan-i-Aam, Diwan-i-Khas, Jahangiri Mahal and Sheesh Mahal.

After Akbar, his grandson Jahangir added many artefacts and monuments to the Agra Fort. He built the tomb of Noorjahan and Sheesh Mahal in the fort.

After Jahangir, his son Shah Jahan made many changes in the Agra Fort. He built the Musamman Burj in the fort, from where he watched the construction of the Taj Mahal.

In 1638, Shah Jahan shifted his capital to Delhi. After this, Agra Fort gradually started falling into decay.

In the 18th and 19th centuries, Agra Fort came under British rule. They used the fort as a military cantonment.

Today, Agra Fort is one of the most popular tourist destinations in India. It is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

Major attractions of Agra Fort
Diwan-e-Aam: This is a big hall where Akbar used to hold his court.
Diwan-e-Khas: This is a small hall where Akbar used to meet his special guests.
Jahangiri Mahal: This was the residence of Jahangir.
Sheesh Mahal: It is a beautiful palace decorated with glass.
Musamman Burj: This is a turret from where Shahjahan watched the construction of Taj Mahal.
Angoori Bagh: It is a beautiful garden which is famous for grapes.
Moti Masjid: It is a beautiful mosque decorated with pearls.
Sher Mandal: It is a monument built in the memory of Humayun.
Importance of Agra Fort
Agra Fort is an important symbol of the history and culture of India. It is an excellent example of Mughal architecture. This fort is one of the most popular tourist destinations in India and is also a UNESCO World Heritage Site.

visit to agra fort
Agra Fort is one of the most popular tourist destinations in India. It remains open throughout the year.

To reach Agra Fort, you can go to Agra by plane, train or bus. Agra Airport is about 7 kilometers from the city. Agra Junction Railway Station City

name: Asutosh Joshi
review_text:
Agra Fort is a majestic testament to Indias historical grandeur. Its imposing red sandstone walls echo with tales of Mughal emperors and intricate architecture. The forts strategic design offers panoramic views of the Taj Mahal, creating a captivating juxtaposition of two iconic landmarks. Walking through the palatial courtyards and opulent chambers, one is immersed in the rich tapestry of Indias royal past. Agra Fort is not just a fortress; its a living chronicle of imperial splendor, making it an essential stop for anyone seeking a profound journey through the annals of Indian history.

name: Rajat Jaithra
review_text:
Red Fort or Red Fort of Agra is a major historical place of India and has many tourist places which attract people to visit. This building was built by the Mughal emperor Shah Jahan and it was his palace. The beauty, grandeur and history of Red Fort, Lal Qila have made it a famous tourist destination. The travelers coming here get the opportunity to enjoy the history of Mughal style, the history of the empire, and Mughal food. Red Fort is situated on the banks of the beautiful lake of Agra and from here one can also see the beautiful view of Taj Mahal. This place provides an experience and knowledge filled journey for the traveling people.

The sea wall of the Red Fort of Agra is a special area which adds to the importance of this historical place. This wall is made of red marble and its greatness lies in the fact that it surrounds the entire Red Fort and ensures its protection. There are small windows and doors in this wall, which act as entry doors and make it safe. The length of the sea wall is approximately 2.5 kilometers and it shows the prestige and power of the Mughal empire. People who visit enjoy the beauty and grandeur of this wall and understand its importance, which is a symbol of the history and grandeur of the Mughal period.
review_translated_text:
Agra ke Lal Qila ya Red Fort, Bharat ka ek pramukh itihasik sthal hai aur yahan par anek darshaniya sthal hain jo yatra karne vale logon ko akarshit karte hain. Is imarate ka nirman Mughal samrat Shah Jahan ne kiya tha aur yeh unka rajgharana tha. Red Fort, Lal Qila ki khoobsurati, bhavyata aur itihas ne ise ek prasiddh paryatan sthal banaya hai. Yahan par aane vale yatriyon ko Mughal shaili ki kala, samrajya ka itihas, aur mughalai bhojan ka anand lene ka avsar milta hai. Red Fort, Agra ki sundar jheel ke kinare sthit hai aur yahan se Taj Mahal ka bhi sundar drishya dekha ja sakta hai. Yatra karne vale logon ke liye yah sthal ek anubhav aur gyan bhara safar pradan karta hai.


Agra ke Lal Qile ke bahari deewar ek visheshatmak kshetra hai jo is itihasik sthal ki mahatta ko aur adhik badha deta hai. Is deewar ka nirman laal sangmarmar se kiya gaya hai aur iski mahatvapurnata ismein hai ki yeh pura Lal Qila ko gher leti hai aur uska suraksha kary nirdharit karti hai. Is deewar mein chhote-chhote khidkiyan aur darwaje hain, jo pravesh dvaron ke roop mein kaam karte hain aur ise surakshit banate hain. Bahari deewar ki lambai lagbhag 2.5 kilometer hai aur yeh Mughal samrajya ki pratibaddhata aur shakti ko darshata hai. Yatra karne vale log is deewar ke saundary aur pratibha ka anand lete hain aur iska mahatva samajhte hain, jo Mughal kal ke itihas aur shaan ka ek prateek hai.

Easy to Locate, but very busy crowded street. Its nearly impossible to drive a vehicle here. You will need a chauffeur to drop you off and pick you up after the visit. The ticket costs Rs.50.00. The maintenance of the site is acceptable. The gardens inside the Agra Fort are very well maintained. Most of the part of the Agra Fort is now not accessible to general public. Make sure you visit the rear side of the Fort, the windows through which its possible to see Taj Mahal. Its said that Shajahan viewed his creation from here through this window when he was kept captive in Agra Fort. Didnt find any toilets inside. So keep that in mind. Tour guides will be there for those who need it.

name: Samiul Alam (SamBoga)
review_text:
Agra Fort is a Must Visit Place if you go to Agra. Its one of the reminiscent of the Mughal Era.It was the main residence of the emperors of the Mughal Dynasty till 1638, when the capital was shifted from Agra to Delhi. The Agra fort is a UNESCO World Heritage site.It is about 2.5 km northwest of its more famous sister monument, the Taj Mahal. You can actually see Tajmahal from this place. You can see the mosques where Shahjahan used to pray, place where he was held captive at the later part of his life, place where citizens used to come etc. If you are into history and architecture and get back into to past, this is the place.

If you come on weekends, make sure to book ticket in advance from online, otherwise there will be huge Que at the front. You can come to Agra from New Delhi either by train or By road using bus/ private car.

Beware of scammers. There are a lot Agra and make sure to not fall for any.

name: Kaushal Kumar
review_text:
The Agra Fort:

1. **Location**: Agra Fort is situated in Agra, Uttar Pradesh, India.

2. **Historical Significance**: It was originally constructed as a military structure by the Mughal Emperor Akbar in the 16th century but later served as a royal residence.

3. **Architecture**: The fort showcases a mix of Islamic, Persian, and Hindu architectural styles, reflecting the diverse influences of the Mughal Empire.

4. **Structure**: The fort is built primarily of red sandstone and covers an area of about 94 acres, surrounded by a double battlemented massive wall of red sandstone. It has four gates: Delhi Gate, Lahore Gate, Amar Singh Gate, and Elephant Gate.

5. **Main Attractions**:
- **Diwan-i-Aam (Hall of Public Audience)**: Where the emperor would address the public.
- **Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience)**: Reserved for private meetings and discussions.
- **Sheesh Mahal (Palace of Mirrors)**: A beautiful hall adorned with intricate mirror work.
- **Khas Mahal**: Private residence of the emperor.
- **Jahangir Palace**: Built by Akbar for his son Jahangir, showcasing Persian influence.

6. **Inscriptions and Decorations**: The fort features inscriptions of verses from the Quran and is decorated with intricate carvings, inlay work, and motifs.

7. **Historical Events**: Agra Fort witnessed several significant historical events, including the imprisonment of Shah Jahan by his son Aurangzeb, who confined him to the fort until his death.

8. **UNESCO World Heritage Site**: Agra Fort was inscribed as a UNESCO World Heritage Site in 1983, recognizing its cultural significance and architectural splendor.

name: blessy babu
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort of Agra, is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in Agra, India. Constructed primarily of red sandstone, it is an architectural marvel and a symbol of the Mughal Empires grandeur. Built by Emperor Akbar in the 16th century, it served as the main residence of the Mughal emperors until the capital was shifted to Delhi. The fort encompasses a vast area, featuring impressive palaces, mosques, gardens, and courtyards, each reflecting the intricate craftsmanship and artistic prowess of the Mughal era. Overall, Agra Fort is an awe-inspiring monument that captivates visitors with its beauty, history, and cultural significance.

name: Piyush Jain
review_text:
The palace to be explored if you really want to understand that how and why India was called as sone ki chidiya and what Mughals had done.

I dont think that the kind of living the Mughal emperor had lived were less than any heaven thing. The harems, the gold plated full room, the stones embedded in those places, the technology water and fountain system, like what else you think of, they were not having.
Question is that, all this was at what cost.

Technologies were there with these people but they never made it commercialised for greater good, development was for king and never for the commoner.

These all things to be read by kids and people to understand that what all we had and what we all lost, so we can again will make this country back to the golden age to complete the cycle.

name: Vikas Yadav (vickey)
review_text:
I recently had the opportunity to visit the Red Kill in Agra. This beautiful red marble fort, famous for its grandeur and historical importance, touched my heart. When I stood on that high hill, the entire view of Agra opened before me, in which the uniqueness of the Taj Mahal was very human. The walls of the Red Fort and the vast collection of palaces make it a unique encounter. The maps of excavation discoveries on its walls, and interviews with the history of the fragrant soil further added to my excitement.

I recently visited Agra Fort, and its grandeur left me in awe. The imposing red sandstone walls and intricate architecture showcase the opulence of the Mughal era. The Diwan-i-Am and Diwan-i-Khas, with their impressive pillars and designs, reflect the historical significance of this UNESCO World Heritage Site. The views of the Yamuna River and the Taj Mahal from Agra Fort add to its charm, making it a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
10-30 min

Reservation recommended
Yes

Construction of the fort is completely masterpiece.

name: shivani sahu
review_text:
Agra fort has beautiful architectural work. People also confuse Agra fort with Red Fort, whereas both are completely different places one in Agra the other one in Delhi respectively. Do not miss out on this place on your next visit to Agra!
Its preferable to book tickets in Advance via Archaeological Survey of India (ASI) website to save some time, because theres a long queue for everything. Even after booking advance tickets you have to wait in a long queue for entry. Plan your visit accordingly, avoid peak periods.
Further, if youre planning to visit Taj Mahal on the same day try not to spend much time here and you may skip tour guides if you have a tight packed schedule.
The best time to visit this place is November to January.

name: Sandeep Singh
review_text:
A must see place if you happen to visit Agra on vacation. It is especially useful on Fridays when all other places including Taj Mahal are closed. Paid parking at @100 is available just across. Entry ticket @40 ( on Friday) is available at the cash counter, not very crowded. It is better to take a guide to understand the place. We bargained for Rs. 200. It takes around 1 hour to see the whole place. You can take a tanga ride for Rs.50 just outside the main entrance. Do NOT go to the leather factory outlets nearby as all are cheats. I bought a leather jacket for 2850 which was proven to be of faux leather later on

name: DeviL VinaY
review_text:
Agra Fort station is located in Agra city of Uttar Pradesh. This station falls in the North Central Railway zone of Indian Railways. This station is very suitable for travelers who want to visit Taj Mahal, Agra Fort and other tourist places.

Agra Fort station is known for its facilities. All the facilities of a railway station are available to the passengers here, which include excellent dining facilities, guarded security, easy seating facilities, reservation counter, ticket machine, and waiting room. The staff here is very nice and ready to help all the passengers.

The condition of Agra Fort station is also quite good and passengers do not face any problem. This station is located in the center of the city which makes it even more convenient.

name: Valentina Audichya
review_text:
An amazing monument to explore. Constructed in red stone as well as white marble. Its panoramic n huge in view, surrounded by strong high fort walls. Entry charges r nominal but proper checking is followed before entering. no outside food is allowed ,only water bottle u can carry. Very comfortable footwear is recommended as u have to walk a lot, plus a hat or mini umbrella is must on a sunny day.
Most of fort area is not approachable to visitors. Still its a marvel to explore. for best experience either u can take a tour guide or u can come prepare with some pre- knowledge from net or books.

name: Diksha Lathwal
review_text:
I visited this place on 25th December (Christmas Day) with my friends. First, I was surprised to see the water drainage system. You know when you are entering the fort, you will see the drainage systen on your left and right side. And after seeing this, one can easily guess the height of the fort. And if this fort is at this great height in 21st Century then it would have been really a great architectural monuments at that time (in 16th century). Not only drainage system, but the architecture, beauty & maintenance of this fort was really attractive. Inside the fort, they are many historical architectures/monuments you will see. But the one& only thing which made me upset was that the rooms/mosque/inner side of all buildings was locked and the tourists were not allowed to see/visit these sections of the fort. Moreover, instead of inscriptions, one must hire a guide to know the real importance of this fort.
Not only for historians/historical perspective, but also for the tourists who have curiosity of visiting & thrilling in their life, this fort is the must one.

name: AZ
review_text: Really recommend to visit this place after visiting the Taj Mahal. After admiring the stellar beauty of the Taj Mahal, you will get to see the history behind it. Book a guide inside the fort, as the get gradually cheaper. Outside, we were offered a guided tour for 2.500 rupees, and inside we negotiated a tour for 500 rupees. We ended up paying the guide 1.500 rupees, as the information he provided was very detailed, and gave us great understanding of the fort. I'd recommend taking a guide anytime!

name: Marcello Villani
review_text: The Red Fort of Agra enchants with its majestic architecture and the history that permeates its walls. The intricate red sandstone details speak to times gone by, while the views of the Taj Mahal are stunning. An immersive visit to a cultural heritage that exudes grandeur and charm.
review_translated_text: Il Forte Rosso di Agra incanta con la sua maestosa architettura e la storia che permea le sue mura. Le intricati dettagli in arenaria rossa narrano epoche passate, mentre il panorama sul Taj Mahal e stupefacente. Una visita immersiva in un patrimonio culturale che trasuda grandezza e fascino.

name: Nishant Shukla
review_text:
Agra fort is a must visit place in Agra. Where the king lives for few years and ruled their place.

The fort complex was designated a UNESCO World Heritage site in 1983.

The fort was commissioned by Akbar in 1565 and reportedly took eight years to construct. The walls of the roughly crescent-shaped structure have a circumference of about 1.5 miles (2.5 km), rise 70 feet (21 metres) high, and are surrounded by a moat

name: jaymin parmar
review_text:
Agra Fort stands as an imposing architectural marvel, steeped in history and cultural significance. As you enter the massive red sandstone walls, the grandeur of this UNESCO World Heritage Site unfolds. The forts intricate design, strategic layout, and the fusion of Persian and Indian architectural styles are nothing short of awe-inspiring. Walking through the Diwan-i-Aam and Diwan-i-Khas, where emperors held court, one can almost feel the echoes of a bygone era. The views of the Taj Mahal from certain vantage points within the fort add an extra layer of charm. Agra Fort, with its rich history and stunning craftsmanship, provides a captivating journey into Indias imperial past, making it a must-visit destination for history enthusiasts and admirers of architectural excellence.

name: Avinash Kumar Chauhan
review_text:
A man made Marvel from Mughal Era. Amazing Craftsmanship & the place is Huge and spread on a very wide area. Entry fee is Rs. 50 per person and Guides are available both inside & outside. Dont take guides outside as they charge more like 900-1000 Rs whether inside they charge like 300-500 Rs. Diwan-e-khas, Diwan-e-aam, Sheesh Mahal, Angoori Bagh and many more attractions are here inside the fort itself. Spend a full day here to enjoy the most out of it. Visited in early Jan 2024

review_text:
Nice sight that is worth a visit. Very spacious and with interesting architecture.
Unfortunately not all areas are accessible...

The only annoying thing is the path to the entrance. First the street vendors and tuk-tuk drivers and then the guides, none of whom let up.

As always, foreigners have to pay more, but they are allowed in through the exit and dont have to wait.

review_translated_text:

Nervig ist nur der Weg bis zum Eingang. Erst die Strassenverkaufer und Tuk-tuk-fahrer und im Anschluss die Guides die alle nicht locker lassen.


Auslander mussen wie immer mehr bezahlen, durfen dafur aber auch durch den Ausgang rein und brauchen nicht zu warten.

review_text:

And don't also dont listen to guide inside fort they will convince you to take them with you and say its not possible to visit whole fort without them, don't listen to them if you really want to enjoy.

name: TAUFEEQ ANSARI
review_text:
A very wonderful and interesting experience, seeing the Red Fort, we go back to the times of the Mughals.
It is not as famous as the Red Fort of Delhi but it is much more beautiful and much bigger than that.

This fort tells the story of the glorious heritage of the Mughals. This UNESCO World Heritage Site is built from the finest red sandstone. It is also known as Agra Fort. It has many beautiful palaces, domed buildings and mosques.

Many parts of this fort still take us to the era of the Mughals.
After watching this, the experience remains with you forever.

Amazing ** Unimaginable

Weekday

name: MANO MATRIX COUNSELING SERVICES
review_text:
Ill be very honest to help you all.
1. NEVER go for a tour guide in the fort, since they will fool you that theyll show you so much in the fort, but no they wont, the charge which I paid for a group of 6 people to a guide is 600 total.
2. 70% AREA is CLOSED in fort and undertaking by army, so practically you get to see only 30% of it, out of this 30% only 15-20% is open, since all rooms are closed, sheesh mehal is closed, and whats left to see is the walls, which used to have gold work on them, which which which in times of Britishers, they have destroyed and took along with them.
3. Extremely crowded on weekends, dont fall for the trap of guides, theyll tell you, that it will take 2-3 hours for you to see the whole fort, NO its a lie, it takes 1 hour maximum!!!! With or without a guide, since the very small portion of the fort is open, rest nothing is functional.
4. Please dont eat anything outside fort area, the food quality is extremely extremely poor and unhealthy, eat something good before you enter there.
Visited on
Weekend

30-60 min

name: Moritz
review_text:
When in Agra, 1 out of 2 or 3 places worth visiting. But dont expect too much... inside there are about 5 information boards and 2-3 viewing points also towards the Taj Mahal... But unfortunately only if youre lucky, as the normal thick smog blocks the view. The chances are better in summer than in winter. Entrance fee 600 Rs for foreigners...15x more than locals...as is often the case. You can save yourself on guides. Great cultural history is not to be expected.
Visited on
Weekday

Wait time
No wait

Reservation recommended
No
review_translated_text: Wenn man in Agra ist, 1 von 2 oder 3 sehenswerten Orten. Aber nicht zu viel erwarten...innen gibt es ca 5 Infotafeln und 2-3 Aussichtspunkte auch Richtung Taj Mahal....Aber leider nur bei Gluck, da normal dicker Smog den Blick verweigert. Im Sommer sind die Chancen besser als im Winter. Eintritt 600 Rs fur Auslander...15x mehr als Einheimische...wie so oft. Guides kann man sich sparen. Grosse Kulturgeschichte ist nicht zu erwarten.

name: Armaj Sombunjaoren
review_text:
A must visit tourist landmark of Jaipur. You can really sense the grandeur from the moment you see it.

I suggest people to visit in the morning before 11 because you can pay 1,100 rupee to ride an elephant up to the fort. The elephant only works from 8-11 in the morning, just 3 hours to prevent animal cruelty. From being up high on the elephant, you can get a spectacular view on your way up to the fort.

The mirror room inside the fort is a must see.

review_text: The red fort of Agra is just amazing as it was shown in movies. The story of Red fort will just kept you bound. The beauty of this monument is mesmerizing. The fort is so big, it is divided in to multiple sections according to the kings name. Every little corner is actually designed so calculatively. If you see a single pillar, then also you will feel the art and work they have done over here. If you are visiting it, then you should go for guide also. They will tell you the details of every single corner. It was an amazing experience.

name: Shubham Biswas
review_text:
Agra Fort is an architectural marvel that left me in awe. The intricate designs, historical significance, and the breathtaking view of the Taj Mahal make it a must-visit. The well-preserved heritage site offers a glimpse into Indias rich past. However, the crowd can be overwhelming, so visiting during non-peak hours is advisable. Overall, a captivating experience that showcases the grandeur of Mughal architecture.

name: Bethany Lo
review_text:
Agra Fort is a must see if you travel to India. The whole place was very impressive, and you can spend hours wondering around. You can feel more of a connection to the history and the Mughal period here than the Taj Mahal as it felt more lived in. Agra Fort was built with bricks in the inner core with sandstone on external surfaces. Some 4,000 builders worked on it daily for eight years, completing it in 1573. It was only during the reign of Akbars grandson, Shah Jahan, that the site took on its current state.

name: Surendra singh Rathore
review_text:
Nestled atop the Aravalli Hills, the formidable Agar Fort stands as a silent sentinel, guarding the secrets of centuries gone by. As you approach its ancient gates, a palpable sense of history envelopes you, transporting you to an era when valor echoed through the rugged landscapes.

The fort, a stoic testament to Rajput architecture, rises majestically against the azure sky, its sandstone walls weathered by time yet bearing the scars of countless tales.

The forts strategic location offers panoramic vistas of the rugged terrain, inviting you to imagine the bygone days when the Rajput warriors stood watch, safeguarding their kingdom against invaders. Each step through the historic passageways is a journey into the soul of Rajasthan, where tales of chivalry and honor resonate through the very stones beneath your feet.

name: PRAVEEN SIVASAMY
review_text:
My visit to the Agra Red Fort was truly unforgettable. The massive red sandstone walls and intricate Mughal architecture showcase the grandeur of India's rich history. Walking through the Diwan-i-Am and Diwan-i-Khas, I could almost feel the presence of past emperors.

The fort offers stunning views of the Yamuna River and a distant glimpse of the Taj Mahal, adding to the experience. Every corner of the fort tells a story, from its beautiful gardens to its regal halls. Its a must-visit for anyone who appreciates history and architecture.

review_text:
Stunning views of the Taj Mahal. Amazing architecture. Wonderful to see such ancient buildings. Watch for guides trying to badger you. If you agree to one at the enterance you will pay too much. They will hound you and drop the price the further you go in.

Stairs are uneven in parts so be careful when stepping in and out of buildings and rooms. Keep belongings to phones camera and water bottles. No tripods. They even took my kids toy. We had to leave it at the cloak room and pick it up later.

name: Praveen Sharma
review_text: The Red Fort in Delhi is a stunning example of Mughal architecture, featuring massive red sandstone walls, intricate carvings, and beautiful gardens. A UNESCO World Heritage Site, it symbolizes Indias rich history and was the main residence of Mughal emperors. The evening light and sound show adds to its charm.

name: A NAYAK
review_text:
Agra Fort, also known as the Red Fort, is located in Agra, Uttar Pradesh. It is a huge fort situated on the banks of river Yamuna. This fort was built by Akbar in 1565. This fort has many beautiful palaces, temples and gardens.
This fort is famous for its architecture and historical importance. This fort is a popular destination for tourists and lakhs of people visit it every year.

review_text:
The Red Fort of Agra is a historical fort built on the banks of the Yamuna River in the city of Agra, Uttar Pradesh. It is also known as Qila-e-Mubarak. This is a big fort of the 16th century, which was built by the Mughal emperor Akbar in 1565 AD. This fort is spread over 94 acres and was given the status of World Heritage Site by UNESCO in the year 1983.

Exploring the Red Fort was like immersing myself in a living history book. From the moment I entered, the grandeur of the Mughal architecture captivated me. Walking through the Diwan-i-Am and Diwan-i-Khas, I could imagine the grandeur of royal gatherings. The intricate carvings and expansive courtyards showcased the empires opulence. Strolling through the gardens, I felt a sense of tranquility amidst the bustling city. The sound and light show in the evening brought the fort to life, narrating tales of its rich past. An experience that left me in awe of Indias architectural and cultural heritage!
Visited on
Public holiday

name: Patricia
review_text:
The Red Fort of Agra is important historical monument. It was built by Akbar and this inspired the Red Fort of Delhi. As the name suggests the fort is made of red sandstone. The fort is surrounded by a moat. The fort was divided into palaces of Akbar, Jehangir and Shah Jehan. The Diwan i Khas does not have a throne like the one at Delhi, but it still has much of the inlay work in the upper section. There are wonderfully carved marble water fountains in most of the inner chambers of the fort. Definitely worth a visit.

name: Ajmal Roshan
review_text:
The Red Fort in Delhi is very similar to Agra Fort, both have the same Mughal architecture, structure, nomenclature etc. Agra Fort is better preserved, and more accessible (as large parts of Red Fort are held by the Indian Army). Fort in Agra is much better then fort at Delhi.

Emperor Shah Jahan commissioned construction of the Red Fort on 12 May 1638, when he decided to shift his capital from Agra to Delhi. Originally red and white, Shah Jahans favourite colours, its design is credited to architect Ustad Ahmad Lahori, who also constructed the Taj Mahal.
It Was Originally White In Colour. ...
It Is A World Heritage Site. ...
Koh-i-Noor Diamond Belonged To The Forts Royal Family. ...
The Entrance Of The Fort Is Called Lahori Gate. ...
The Rang Mahal Is Situated In The Premises Of The Fort. ...
Its Original Name Was Qila-E-Mubarak

name: William Shepherd
review_text:
The Red Fort in Agra is like a trip back in time, full of history and beauty. The fancy buildings made by Shah Jahan with marble are amazing, showing off really detailed artwork. Being close to the Taj Mahal makes it even more special, offering stunning views. Its sad to hear about tourists causing damage in some places, like Shah Jahans private spot, the Seesh Mahal, which is now closed. But, overall, they do a good job taking care of the Red Fort, making you feel like youre in a fancy old-time palace.

name: Rabin upadhaya
review_text:
Agra Fort is another wonderful and historical place to visit after Taj Mahal. Dont forget to click pictures and take videos. Carry a camera and use phones for photos and videos. Also, please take something for the squirrels as it will be photogenic to feed them from your hand.
Take a day trip for Taj Mahal, Agra Fort, and Fatehpur Sikri. The taxi will take about 2500 INR for the day trip. Beware of local guides.

name: Pragati Gautam
review_text:
Red fort tells us about our ancient heritage..It is the place where Shah Jahan was kept as a prisioner by his son for cutting the hands of lakhs of workers who were involved in building the Taj Mahal

This is the only place from where Taj Mahal is visible.It is said that Shah Jahan used to see Taj mahal from this fort when he was in prison.

name: Jayesh Jani (Kann)
review_text:
The historical monument, Agra Fort was built on the 16th century. It will stand near the gardens of Taj Mahal. It was built by Akbar and covers a total area of 380,000 square meters. More than 4000 workers and 8 years of hard work resulted in Agra Fort. Many impressive structures like Moti Masjid, Jahangir Mahal, Machchhi Bhawan, Diwan-I-Am, Diwan-I-Khass and Khas Mahal are present inside the Agra Fort.

Agra Fort
Agra Fort is also called as a walled city and is also considered as the UNESCO World Heritage Site. It is considered as a tourist attractions and attracts many tourists all over the world. It is the main residence during the region of Akbar. It lost its status of the main residence after the Mughal dynasty was replaced to Delhi from Agra. It is located at a distance of 2.5 kilometres from Taj Mahal.

name: Virsa Vibbes
review_text:
The Red Fort of Agra is a UNESCO World Heritage Site located in Agra, India. It is an architectural marvel that was built during the Mughal era and served as the residence of the Mughal Emperors until the 17th century.

The Red Fort was constructed by the Mughal Emperor Akbar, who began its construction in 1565. However, the forts final layout and finishing touches were given by Emperor Shah Jahan, who is better known for his contribution to the majestic Taj Mahal.

The Red Fort of Agra is constructed from red sandstone, and its walls are surrounded by a moat. The forts architecture is a mix of Persian and Hindu styles, with intricate carvings adorning the walls.

The forts main entrance is through the Amar Singh Gate, which leads to the innermost part of the fort, known as the Diwan-i-Am or the Hall of Public Audience. It is a grand hall with a domed roof, where the Emperor would meet the public and listen to their grievances.

Another impressive feature of Red Fort is the Diwan-i-Khas, or the Hall of Private Audience. It is a beautifully decorated chamber where the Emperor would hold private meetings with his ministers and courtiers.

The Khas Mahal is another noteworthy building inside the fort complex. It was the Emperor's private quarters, and it was extensively decorated with intricate inlay work and paintings.

The Sheesh Mahal or the Glass Palace is another must-see attraction in the fort. It is a beautiful chamber with walls and ceilings covered in tiny mirrors that emit a dazzling effect when light is reflected upon them.

In conclusion, the Red Fort of Agra is an architectural masterpiece that is known for its stunning design, intricate artwork, and rich history. It is a must-visit destination for tourists visiting Agra and provides an excellent insight into the glory of the Mughal era.

name: Kavita Verma
review_text:
This historic fortification was built by the Mughal Emperor Akbar in the 16th century and served as the main residence of the Mughal dynasty until the mid-17th century. The fort is made of red sandstone and is known for its impressive architectural design and intricate carvings.

The fort is made of red sandstone and covers an area of approximately 94 acres and the fort complex includes several buildings, including the Diwan-i-Am (Hall of Public Audience), the Diwan-i-Khas (Hall of Private Audience), the Moti Masjid (Pearl Mosque), and the Jahangir Palace. The fort also has beautiful gardens and a stunning view of the nearby Taj Mahal.

The Diwan-i-Khas or the Hall of Private Audience is a beautiful chamber, designed for private meetings between the emperor and select members of the court. The hall has impressive marble columns, a beautifully crafted throne and is decorated with precious stones.

The Diwan-i-Am or the Hall of Public Audience is a vast courtyard where the emperor used to meet his subjects and listen to their grievances. The Jahangir Palace is a stunning building with intricate carvings and beautiful gardens. The Khas Mahal is a luxurious palace with beautiful marble pavilions, private courtyards, and an impressive water system. The Sheesh Mahal or the Palace of Mirrors is a breathtaking chamber, decorated with intricate mirror-work and colored glass.

Today, the Red Fort of Agra is a UNESCO World Heritage Site and a popular tourist attraction. Visitors can explore the fort and its various buildings, and learn about the history of the Mughal Empire and the city of Agra.

name: Sammed Chougule
review_text:
The Red Fort in Agra is one of the most iconic monuments in India. Constructed by the Mughal Emperor Shah Jahan in the mid-17th century, this majestic structure is a symbol of Indias rich history and cultural heritage.

The Red Fort is a testament to the architectural genius of the Mughals. The fort is made of red sandstone and features intricate carvings, delicate filigree work, and stunning arches. The fort is divided into several sections, each with its own unique architecture and design. Visitors can explore the various courtyards, palaces, and mosques within the forts walls, all of which are adorned with intricate carvings and beautiful decorations.

One of the most impressive features of the Red Fort is the Diwan-i-Am or the Hall of Public Audience. This magnificent hall is a vast open space, surrounded by massive red sandstone columns, and was used by the emperor to address the public. Visitors can stand in the center of the hall and imagine the emperor speaking to the masses.

The fort also features several beautiful gardens and water features, including the Anguri Bagh or the Grape Garden, which was once used to grow grapes for the emperors wine.

Overall, a visit to the Red Fort in Agra is an unforgettable experience. The sheer size and beauty of the fort, combined with its rich history and cultural significance, make it a must-visit destination for anyone interested in Indias past and present. If youre planning a trip to Agra, be sure to include the Red Fort in your itinerary.

name: Shailesh Kadam
review_text:
Mughal emperor Shahjahan built the Red Fort as a palace for his capital Shahjahanabad. Red Fort is famous for its huge walls. The construction of the fort was completed in ten years between 1638 and 1648. The Red Fort or Lal Qila, located in the historic, fortified area of   Delhi, Old Delhi, is built of red sandstone. The fort is called the Red Fort, because of the scarlet-red color of its walls. This historical fort was selected as a World Heritage Site by UNESCO in the year 2007. [1] The Red Fort located in the capital of India, Delhi, is a symbol of the countrys pride and independence. Red Fort is included in the list of historical monuments world heritage and is one of the major tourist destinations of India. People come from all corners of the world to see the beauty, grandeur and attraction of the Red Fort and admire its royal structure and unique architecture.

This royal fort is not only the political center of the Mughal emperors but it was also the ceremonial centre, which was ruled by the rulers of the Mughal dynasty for about 200 years. The Red Fort, which was a witness to the countrys war of independence, is a unique and unique example of Mughal period architecture, creativity and beauty.

There is also a very beautiful museum inside this grand fort built in 1648 AD. This grand fort, spread over about 250 acres of land, tells the story of the deep struggle against the Mughal monarchy and the British. The history of this fort, which is considered the national pride of India, is very interesting.

Some people also believe that the Red Fort was built by Prithvi Raj Chauhans maternal grandfather Shri Anang Pal Tomar II in 1060.

name: A R
review_text:
Agra Fort is a UNESCO declared World Heritage Site. This fort is located in Agra city of Uttar Pradesh state of India. The world famous monument Taj Mahal is present only about 2.5 kilometers north-west of it. Some historians consider it better to call this fort a walled palace city. It is the most important fort of India. Indias Mughal emperors Babar, Humayun, Akbar, Jahangir, Shahjahan and Aurangzeb lived here.

It was originally a brick fort, its first description comes in 1080 AD, when it was captured by the army of Mahmud Ghaznavi. Sikandar Lodi (1487-1517), was the first Sultan of Delhi Sultanate who visited Agra and got this fort repaired in 1504 AD and stayed in this fort. Sikandar Lodi made it the capital in 1506 AD and ruled the country from here. He also died in this fort in 1517. Later his son Ibrahim Lodi held the throne for nine years, until he was killed in the First Battle of Panipat (1526). He built many places, mosques and wells here during his time.

After Panipat, the Mughals captured this fort as well as its immense wealth. There was also a diamond in this property which later became famous by the name of Kohinoor diamond. Then Babar came in place of Ibrahim in this fort. He built a stepwell here. Humayuns coronation also took place here in 1530. Humayun was defeated by Sher Shah Suri in Bilgram in the same year and the fort was captured by him. This fort was occupied by the Afghans for five years, who were finally defeated by the Mughals in the Second Battle of Panipat in 1556.

Seeing its central position, Akbar decided to make it his capital and came here in 1558. Its historian Abul Fazal has written that this fort was a brick fort, whose name was Badalgarh. It was in a dilapidated condition at that time and Akbar had to get it rebuilt, which he did with red sandstone. Its foundation was laid by great architects. It was built with bricks from inside, and red sandstone was used for the outer covering. Fourteen lakh forty four thousand artisans and laborers worked hard for eight years in its construction, then it was completed in the year 1573.

Akbars grandson Shahjahan brought this place to its present form. There is also a myth that when Shahjahan built the Taj Mahal for his beloved wife, he wanted the buildings to be made of white marble inlaid with gold and precious gems. During the construction of the fort, he also demolished many old buildings and buildings, so that the fort could have buildings built by him.

Towards the end of his life, Shah Jahan was imprisoned in this fort by his son Aurangzeb, a punishment that was not severe considering the luxury of the forts palaces. It is also said that Shah Jahan died in the Musamman Burj of the fort, overlooking the Taj Mahal. A very beautiful view of the Taj Mahal is visible from the marble windows of this tower.

This fort also became a battlefield during the First Indian War of Independence in 1857. After which the rule of the British East India Company ended in India, and Britain continued to rule directly for almost a century. After which we got independence directly.

name: Dr. Bahadur Singh FRAI
review_text:
The Red Fort of Agra is a remarkable monument that showcases the magnificent Mughal architecture of India. Commissioned by Emperor Akbar in the 16th century, this fort stands tall with its majestic red stone structure that speaks volumes of the grandeur and opulence of the Mughal era.

I had the opportunity to visit this fort during my university trip to Agra, and I was awestruck by its beauty and grandeur. The fort has several palaces inside, each built for a specific purpose. One of my favourites was the palace where Akbar announced his new religion, Din-e-Elahi, which combined the best of different faiths popular in Asia. It was fascinating to see how the emperors vision of a religion that would unite people of different faiths was manifested in the architecture of the palace.

The fort also has other notable buildings, such as the Panch Mahal, a five-story palace built exclusively for queens, and the beautiful pond where Tansen used to sing for the emperor. The architecture is purely Mughal, with Persian influences prevalent throughout the fort.

As a visitor, I found the fort to be very well-maintained and clean, thanks to the efforts of the Indian and state governments. However, one has to be cautious of the local guides, who may try to scam visitors.

In conclusion, the Red Fort of Agra is an excellent tourist destination that offers a glimpse into the grandeur and opulence of the Mughal era. With its stunning architecture, fascinating history, and well-maintained premises, the fort is a must-visit for anyone traveling to Agra.

name: Aashish Singh
review_text: The Red Fort is a historical fortification in the old Delhi area. Shah Jahan constructed it in the year 1639 as a result of a capital shift from Agra to Delhi. After the British left India, the first Prime Minister, Jawahar Lal Nehru raised the National Flag from Lahori Gate and since then, every Independence and Republic day witnesses the Prime Minister unfurling the National Flag and giving his ceremonial speech at the Red Fort.The best time to visit this destination is during the months of September- March, when the weather is pleasant.The nearest Metro Station is Chandini Chowk on the Yellow Line. You can hire an autorickshaw or a taxi from the metro station. Also, you can reach Red Fort from any part of the city through the DTC buses that ply regularly on this route.

name: Shri ram Patidar
review_text:
Red Fort is nice place . My all friends enjoy and happy  time spend . We have many time visit this place . We like to see this place . We make fun here . We have enjoy . We are click many pictures .
I like this place ground. This place have many architectural things .The entry to Agra Fort is allowed through the Amar Singh Gate only. Some portion of this fort is used by the Indian Army. The public access to that part has been prohibited. So you can not see that area.

However as this fort is very expansive and contains many buildings that are worth a visit so you can very well check them out.

On visiting the Agra Fort, you will come across Diwan-i-Am or the Hall of Public Audience. This hall with numerous pillars is said to be erected by Shah Jahan in the year 1628. On heading little forward, you will see Royal Pavilions abounding in elegant mosques including Nagina Masjid and Mina Masjid, palaces like Macchi Bhavan, Khas Mahal, Shish Mahal and Shah Jahani Mahal and the Zenana Mina Bazaar.

review_text: Superb. Located opposite to Agra Fort railway station. Entry gate is around 1.5 km from the Agra Fort railway station. name: Manjusha 91
review_text: Agra fort is a popular historical fort in the city of agra,uttar pradesh,india.agra fort was known to be the main residence of the emperors of the mughal agra fort is one of the biggest forts of india,present fort has been made by 3rd mughal ruller akbar,but before mughals there used to be a fort of hindu king badal singh,and the fort used to be called badlgarah fort.in 1556 3rd mughal ruller 3rd gates were provided on all the sides,one was the khizri gate which opened on to the river .two of the gates of the fort are notable the delhi gate and the lahore gate.the lahore gate is popularly known as the amar singh gate for amar singh rathore.plz to visit in agra fort
